const ECONOMICS_EDEXCEL_B_PRACTICE = {
  '1.1': {
    name: 'How Markets Work & Surplus',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term "effective demand".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Demand backed by the ability and willingness to pay at a given price.' },
      { q: 'Define equilibrium price.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The price at which quantity demanded equals quantity supplied, with no tendency to change.' },
      { q: 'State one factor that would cause a demand curve to shift to the right.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid factor, e.g., increase in consumer income (for a normal good), increase in population, successful advertising, rise in price of a substitute, fall in price of a complement.' },
      { q: 'Calculate PED if a 20% price increase leads to a 10% fall in quantity demanded.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Correct formula (% change in Qd / % change in P). 1 mark: Correct answer of -0.5 (or 0.5 ignoring sign).' },
      { q: 'Using a supply and demand diagram, show the effect of an indirect tax on equilibrium price and quantity.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly labelled supply and demand diagram with initial equilibrium. 1 mark: Supply curve shifts vertically upward by the amount of the tax (S to S+tax). 1 mark: New equilibrium shows higher price (though not by full amount of tax) and lower quantity.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a fall in the price of coffee might lead to a decrease in demand for tea.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Coffee and tea are substitutes. 1 mark: A fall in the price of coffee makes it relatively cheaper, so consumers switch from tea to coffee, reducing demand for tea (shifting tea demand curve left).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, illustrate how consumer surplus is affected by a rise in the market price.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn demand curve with consumer surplus shaded at original price. 1 mark: Higher price shown with reduced consumer surplus area. 1 mark: Explanation that consumer surplus falls because fewer consumers are willing to pay the higher price and remaining consumers pay more.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the cross elasticity of demand if a 5% rise in the price of Coca-Cola causes a 15% rise in demand for Pepsi.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Correct formula (% change in Qd of good B / % change in price of good A). 1 mark: Correct answer of +3.0, indicating strong substitutes.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the price elasticity of demand for petrol is likely to differ between the short run and the long run.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: PED is inelastic in the short run. 1 mark: Because motorists have limited alternatives to driving and cannot quickly change their car or habits. 1 mark: PED becomes more elastic in the long run. 1 mark: Because consumers can switch to electric vehicles, use public transport, move closer to work, or car-share, all of which reduce dependence on petrol.' },
      { q: 'Draw a diagram showing both consumer surplus and producer surplus at market equilibrium.', marks: 2, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly labelled supply and demand diagram with equilibrium. 1 mark: Consumer surplus correctly identified as area above price and below demand curve; producer surplus as area below price and above supply curve.' },
      { q: 'Explain what happens to total revenue when price is reduced for a good with elastic demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Total revenue increases. 1 mark: Because the percentage increase in quantity demanded exceeds the percentage fall in price, so the gain in revenue from extra sales outweighs the revenue lost from the lower price per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why agricultural markets often experience greater price volatility than manufactured goods markets.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Supply of agricultural goods is inelastic in the short run (time to grow crops). 1 mark: Supply is subject to unpredictable shocks (weather, disease). 1 mark: Demand for food tends to be inelastic (necessity). 1 mark: The combination of inelastic supply and demand means any shift causes large price changes, while manufactured goods have more elastic supply due to inventories and adjustable production.' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of using price elasticity of demand estimates for business decision-making.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: PED estimates are based on ceteris paribus assumptions that rarely hold in practice. 1 mark: Developed explanation, e.g., competitors may respond to price changes, consumer preferences may shift, or the estimate may be based on historical data that is no longer relevant to current market conditions.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain the effect of a government subsidy on producer surplus.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with supply shifting right due to subsidy. 1 mark: Producer surplus area identified (below the new effective price received by producers, above original supply curve). 1 mark: Explanation that producer surplus increases because producers receive a higher effective price (market price plus subsidy per unit) and sell more units.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the multiplier if the marginal propensity to import is 0.2, the marginal rate of tax is 0.2, and the marginal propensity to save is 0.1.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: MPW = MPS + MRT + MPM = 0.1 + 0.2 + 0.2 = 0.5. 1 mark: Multiplier = 1/0.5 = 2.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the supply of housing is price inelastic in the short run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: It takes a long time to build new houses (planning permission, construction). 1 mark: Land supply is fixed, especially in urban areas. 1 mark: Therefore even if house prices rise significantly, the quantity of housing cannot increase quickly, making supply inelastic in the short run (though more elastic in the long run as new developments are completed).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain the concept of a price floor and its effect on the market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly labelled supply and demand diagram. 1 mark: Price floor shown above equilibrium price. 1 mark: Surplus (excess supply) identified at the floor price. 1 mark: Explanation that at the higher price, quantity supplied exceeds quantity demanded, creating a surplus that the government may need to purchase or allow to go unsold.' },
      { q: 'Explain the significance of income elasticity of demand for a firm selling luxury goods during a recession.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Luxury goods have YED > 1 (income elastic). 1 mark: During a recession, incomes fall. 1 mark: Therefore demand for luxury goods falls by a greater percentage than the fall in income, meaning the firm experiences a disproportionately large drop in sales and revenue.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between a movement along and a shift of the supply curve.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A movement along is caused by a change in the price of the good itself (change in quantity supplied). 1 mark: A shift is caused by a change in a non-price factor such as costs of production, technology, or government policy (change in supply).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the concept of joint supply is relevant to the oil market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Joint supply means that producing one good automatically produces another (e.g., crude oil refining produces petrol, diesel, kerosene, and other by-products). 1 mark: An increase in demand for one product (petrol) leads to increased supply of all joint products, which may cause the price of by-products to fall if their demand has not increased correspondingly.' },
      { q: 'Define the term "derived demand".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Demand for a factor of production or intermediate good that arises from (is derived from) the demand for the final good it helps to produce, e.g., demand for steel is derived from demand for cars.' },
      { q: 'State one condition necessary for a good to have perfectly inelastic demand.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid condition, e.g., the good has no substitutes, it is an absolute necessity (e.g., life-saving medication), or it represents a negligible proportion of income.' },
      { q: 'Calculate income elasticity of demand if income rises by 8% and quantity demanded rises by 12%.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Correct formula (% change in Qd / % change in income). 1 mark: Correct answer of +1.5, indicating a luxury/superior good (YED > 1).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a maximum price (price ceiling) set below the equilibrium on a market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly labelled supply and demand diagram with equilibrium. 1 mark: Maximum price shown below equilibrium price. 1 mark: Shortage (excess demand) identified at the ceiling price. 1 mark: Explanation that at the lower price, quantity demanded exceeds quantity supplied, creating a shortage that may lead to queuing, rationing, or black markets.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a normal good and an inferior good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A normal good has a positive income elasticity of demand - demand increases as income rises (e.g., organic food, restaurant meals). 1 mark: An inferior good has a negative income elasticity of demand - demand falls as income rises because consumers switch to higher-quality alternatives (e.g., value-brand products, bus travel).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the price of concert tickets for popular artists often rises in secondary markets.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Supply is perfectly inelastic as venue capacity is fixed. 1 mark: Demand exceeds supply at the face-value price, creating excess demand. 1 mark: Secondary markets (resale) allow prices to rise to the market-clearing level, with the difference between face value and resale price representing consumer willingness to pay above the administered price.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how a subsidy to consumers differs in effect from a subsidy to producers.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Consumer subsidy shown as demand curve shifting right (willingness to pay increases). 1 mark: Producer subsidy shown as supply curve shifting right (costs effectively reduced). 1 mark: Both result in higher equilibrium quantity. 1 mark: Key difference explained: consumer subsidy raises the market price received by producers and increases quantity; producer subsidy lowers the market price paid by consumers and increases quantity. The distribution of benefit depends on relative elasticities.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a Giffen good has an upward-sloping demand curve.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A Giffen good is an inferior good where the income effect outweighs the substitution effect. 1 mark: When price rises, the substitution effect leads consumers to buy less, but the income effect (real income falls) leads them to buy more of this cheap staple. 1 mark: Because the positive income effect dominates the negative substitution effect, quantity demanded rises as price rises, creating a positively sloped demand curve.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the price elasticity of supply if a 10% price increase leads to a 25% increase in quantity supplied.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Correct formula (% change in Qs / % change in P). 1 mark: Correct answer of 2.5, indicating elastic supply.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the burden of an indirect tax falls more heavily on consumers when demand is price inelastic.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: When demand is inelastic, consumers are less responsive to price changes and have few alternatives. 1 mark: Producers can pass on most of the tax as a higher price without losing many sales. 1 mark: Therefore consumers bear a larger proportion of the tax incidence through higher prices, while producers bear less because their revenue per unit falls only slightly.' },
      { q: 'Explain why composite demand for crude oil makes its price sensitive to changes in any one of its uses.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Composite demand means a good is demanded for multiple distinct purposes (crude oil is used for petrol, plastics, heating, aviation fuel). 1 mark: An increase in demand from any one use shifts the overall demand curve right, putting upward pressure on price and potentially reducing availability for other uses.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the deadweight loss created by an indirect tax on a competitive market.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn supply and demand diagram with supply shifting up by the tax amount. 1 mark: Tax revenue rectangle identified (tax per unit multiplied by new quantity). 1 mark: Deadweight loss triangle identified between old and new equilibrium quantities, representing the lost consumer and producer surplus from transactions that no longer take place.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the demand curve for a firm in a perfectly competitive market is perfectly elastic.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: There are many sellers offering identical (homogeneous) products and buyers have perfect information. 1 mark: If a firm raises its price even slightly above the market price, it loses all its customers to competitors; there is no need to lower price as it can sell as much as it wants at the market price.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of competitive demand and give an example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Competitive demand (substitutes in demand) occurs when two goods serve a similar purpose, so an increase in the price of one leads to an increase in demand for the other. 1 mark: Valid example, e.g., butter and margarine, Uber and conventional taxis, streaming services (Netflix and Disney+).' },
      { q: 'Explain how the concept of elasticity of supply is relevant to a firm deciding whether to respond to a price increase.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If supply is elastic, the firm can quickly increase output to take advantage of the higher price. 1 mark: If supply is inelastic, the firm cannot easily increase output due to capacity constraints or factor immobility. 1 mark: The firm must assess whether spare capacity, raw materials, and labour are available before committing to increased production, as failing to respond means lost revenue while overcommitting may raise costs.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the welfare effects of removing a subsidy from a market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with subsidised equilibrium (supply shifted right by subsidy). 1 mark: Removal of subsidy shifts supply left back to original position. 1 mark: New equilibrium shows higher price and lower quantity. 1 mark: Consumer surplus falls, producer surplus falls, but government expenditure on subsidy is saved; net welfare effect depends on whether the subsidy was correcting a market failure or creating distortions.' },
      { q: 'Explain why knowledge of income elasticity of demand is useful for a supermarket planning its product range.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If local incomes are expected to rise, the supermarket should stock more income-elastic goods (luxury/premium products) as demand will rise proportionally more. 1 mark: If a recession is expected, demand for inferior goods (value brands) will increase while luxury items decline. 1 mark: Understanding YED allows the supermarket to adjust shelf space, stock levels, and marketing to match expected demand patterns and maximise revenue.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between individual demand and market demand.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Individual demand is the quantity of a good one consumer is willing and able to buy at each price. 1 mark: Market demand is the horizontal summation of all individual demand curves in the market, representing total quantity demanded by all consumers at each price.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the market for second-hand cars may suffer from the "lemons problem".', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Asymmetric information exists because sellers know the true quality of their car but buyers do not. 1 mark: Buyers offer an average price reflecting the mix of good and bad cars. 1 mark: Owners of good cars withdraw from the market (price too low), leaving disproportionately poor-quality cars ("lemons"), which drives quality and prices down further - potentially causing market failure where good-quality second-hand cars are not traded.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the supply of skilled labour (e.g., surgeons) is more price inelastic than the supply of unskilled labour.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Training to become a surgeon takes many years (7-10+ years of medical education and specialisation). 1 mark: Even if wages rise significantly, the supply of new surgeons cannot increase quickly because of the lengthy training pipeline. 1 mark: Unskilled labour requires little or no training, so supply can respond to wage changes much faster through workers entering from other occupations or inactivity, making it more elastic.' }
    ]
  },
  '1.2': {
    name: 'Market Failure & Government Intervention',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term "externality".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: A cost or benefit that affects a third party not directly involved in a transaction, which is not reflected in the market price.' },
      { q: 'State one example of a positive externality of consumption.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid example, e.g., vaccination (herd immunity benefits non-vaccinated), education (more productive workforce benefits employers and society), home improvements (raise neighbourhood property values).' },
      { q: 'Define a merit good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A good that is under-consumed in a free market relative to the socially optimal level. 1 mark: Due to information failure (consumers underestimate benefits) and/or positive externalities of consumption.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the welfare loss caused by a negative externality of production.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with MPC (private supply) and MSC (social supply) curves, with MSC above MPC. 1 mark: Free market equilibrium at MPC = MPB shown, and socially optimal output at MSC = MSB shown. 1 mark: Welfare loss triangle identified between MSC and MPC from socially optimal output to free market output.' },
      { q: 'Explain why public goods are unlikely to be provided by the private sector.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Public goods are non-excludable - firms cannot prevent non-payers from benefiting. 1 mark: This creates the free rider problem - rational consumers will not pay if they can benefit without paying. 1 mark: Without revenue from consumers, there is no profit incentive for private firms to supply the good, leading to market failure (missing market).' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of using a Pigouvian tax to correct a negative externality.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - it internalises the external cost by making polluters pay, moving output towards the socially optimal level using the price mechanism. 1 mark: Development, e.g., it maintains consumer/producer choice while providing incentive to reduce harmful activity. 1 mark: Disadvantage - it is difficult to calculate the exact monetary value of the externality. 1 mark: Development, e.g., if set too low it under-corrects, if too high it over-corrects, and the externality may vary by location, time, and context.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the term "government failure" and give one example.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Government failure occurs when government intervention results in a greater misallocation of resources than the original market failure. 1 mark: Valid example, e.g., the Common Agricultural Policy leading to butter mountains and wine lakes through excessive minimum price guarantees. 1 mark: Explanation of why this represents a worse outcome than the original market failure.' },
      { q: 'Explain how asymmetric information leads to market failure in the insurance market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Asymmetric information means one party has more knowledge than the other. 1 mark: Adverse selection - high-risk individuals are more likely to buy insurance, but insurers cannot distinguish them from low-risk buyers. 1 mark: This drives up premiums, causing low-risk individuals to drop out, potentially leading to market collapse or significantly higher prices than necessary.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how a subsidy on education can move consumption towards the socially optimal level.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing MPB and MSB curves with MSB to the right of MPB (positive externality). 1 mark: Free market equilibrium at MPB = MSC shown. 1 mark: Subsidy shifts supply right (or effectively reduces price to consumers). 1 mark: New output closer to socially optimal level (where MSB = MSC), with explanation that the subsidy reduces price, encouraging more consumption of education.' },
      { q: 'State two characteristics of a common resource and explain why they lead to overuse.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Rivalrous (one person\'s use reduces availability for others). 1 mark: Non-excludable (difficult to prevent access). 1 mark: These lead to overuse because each individual gains the full benefit of consumption but shares the cost of depletion with all users, creating an incentive to over-exploit (tragedy of the commons).' },
      { q: 'Explain how property rights can be used to solve the problem of overfishing.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Without property rights, fish stocks are common resources subject to overexploitation. 1 mark: Assigning property rights (e.g., Individual Transferable Quotas) gives owners an incentive to manage stocks sustainably for long-term profit. 1 mark: Owners will only harvest at a sustainable rate because depletion reduces the value of their asset, aligning private incentives with social optimum.' },
      { q: 'Explain why information failure is considered a type of market failure.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: When consumers or producers lack full information, they make suboptimal decisions. 1 mark: This leads to misallocation of resources - goods may be over- or under-consumed relative to the socially optimal level (e.g., consumers smoking because they underestimate health risks).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a nudge policy might reduce sugar consumption.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Definition/identification of nudge - altering choice architecture without banning options. 1 mark: Example applied to sugar, e.g., placing fruit at eye level and sugary snacks on lower shelves in shops, or using traffic light labelling to highlight sugar content. 1 mark: Explanation of mechanism - exploits behavioural biases (status quo bias, salience) to make healthier choices easier without restricting freedom.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of moral hazard and give an economic example.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Moral hazard occurs when one party takes more risks because they know another party bears the cost. 1 mark: Valid example, e.g., banks taking excessive risks knowing they are "too big to fail" and will be bailed out by the government. 1 mark: Explanation of why this is a market failure - it distorts incentives, leading to excessive risk-taking and potential systemic costs borne by society.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the optimal level of pollution is not zero.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Reducing pollution to zero would require stopping all economic activity that creates pollution. 1 mark: The marginal cost of reducing pollution increases as pollution approaches zero (diminishing returns to abatement). 1 mark: The socially optimal level is where the marginal social benefit of the polluting activity equals the marginal social cost of pollution - some pollution is accepted because the output produced is valued by society.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why regulation might be preferred to taxation for controlling dangerous pollutants.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Regulation provides certainty about the maximum level of pollution (e.g., outright ban or strict limit). 1 mark: This is important for dangerous pollutants (toxic chemicals, radioactive waste) where any exposure above a threshold causes serious irreversible harm, and a tax might not reduce emissions sufficiently if demand for the polluting activity is inelastic.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the difference between private and social costs for a factory that pollutes a river.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with MSC above MPC. 1 mark: The vertical distance between MSC and MPC represents the marginal external cost (pollution damage to third parties). 1 mark: Free market produces at MPC = MPB (too much), while socially optimal is at MSC = MSB (less output), with the difference representing overproduction.' },
      { q: 'Explain why government provision of street lighting is justified on economic grounds.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Street lighting is a public good (non-rival and non-excludable). 1 mark: The free rider problem means no private firm would profitably supply it as they cannot charge individual users. 1 mark: Yet it provides significant social benefits (safety, crime reduction), so government provision funded through taxation corrects this market failure.' },
      { q: 'Explain one unintended consequence of the UK plastic bag charge.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid unintended consequence identified, e.g., increased sales of thicker "bags for life" that are used once and discarded, actually increasing total plastic weight. 1 mark: Explanation of why this undermines the policy objective or creates a new problem (heavier bags take longer to decompose, or consumers substitute with paper bags that have higher carbon footprints in production).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a public good and a merit good.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A public good is non-rival and non-excludable, leading to complete market failure (non-provision by the market). 1 mark: A merit good is rivalrous and excludable but is under-consumed due to information failure and positive externalities - the market provides it but at below the socially optimal level.' },
      { q: 'Define the term "demerit good".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: A good that is over-consumed in a free market relative to the socially optimal level, because consumers overestimate private benefits or underestimate private costs, and/or negative externalities are generated.' },
      { q: 'State one example of a negative externality of consumption.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid example, e.g., passive smoking from cigarette consumption, alcohol-related antisocial behaviour, congestion from car use, noise from loud music.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the welfare gain from correcting the under-consumption of a merit good.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with MPB below MSB (positive externality/information failure). 1 mark: Free market output at MPB = MPC shown. 1 mark: Socially optimal output at MSB = MSC shown. 1 mark: Welfare gain triangle identified as the area between MSB and MSC from free market output to socially optimal output, representing the net social benefit of additional consumption.' },
      { q: 'Explain why tradable pollution permits may be more efficient than a flat emissions limit.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Permits set a total cap on emissions but allow firms to trade permits among themselves. 1 mark: Firms that can reduce pollution cheaply will do so and sell surplus permits; firms facing high abatement costs will buy permits. 1 mark: This means pollution reduction occurs where it is cheapest, achieving the target at lowest overall economic cost, unlike flat limits which impose equal burden regardless of each firm\'s abatement cost.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a sugar tax is an example of an indirect tax designed to correct a market failure.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The sugar tax raises the price of sugary drinks to reflect the external costs they impose (obesity, diabetes, NHS costs). 1 mark: It internalises the externality by making consumers face the full social cost. 1 mark: Higher prices reduce consumption towards the socially optimal level and incentivise producers to reformulate products with less sugar, correcting the over-consumption caused by information failure and negative externalities.' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of cost-benefit analysis (CBA) as a tool for government decision-making.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: It is difficult to assign accurate monetary values to intangible costs and benefits such as the value of a human life, environmental amenity, or community cohesion. 1 mark: Different assumptions and methodologies can produce very different results, making CBA susceptible to manipulation and bias, and the process may undervalue benefits to future generations or marginalised groups who are underrepresented.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Coase theorem suggests externalities can be resolved without government intervention.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The theorem states that if property rights are well-defined and transaction costs are low, private bargaining can reach an efficient outcome regardless of the initial assignment of rights. 1 mark: The affected party and the polluter can negotiate compensation or payment to reach the socially optimal output. 1 mark: Limitation: in practice, high transaction costs, large numbers of affected parties, and difficulties in identifying and enforcing rights mean the Coase theorem rarely works for major externalities like air pollution.' },
      { q: 'Explain why behavioural economics challenges the assumption of rational consumer behaviour.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Traditional economics assumes consumers maximise utility with perfect information processing. 1 mark: Behavioural economics shows consumers exhibit systematic biases such as present bias (overvaluing immediate gratification), loss aversion, anchoring, and status quo bias. 1 mark: These biases lead to predictable deviations from rational choice, e.g., consumers failing to save for retirement or choosing unhealthy food despite knowing the risks, justifying nudge interventions.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a negative externality of consumption on market equilibrium.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with MPB above MSB (MSB lies to the left of MPB). 1 mark: Free market equilibrium at MPB = MPC shown, with socially optimal output at MSB = MSC shown. 1 mark: Welfare loss triangle identified between MPB and MSB from socially optimal to free market output, showing over-consumption relative to the social optimum.' },
      { q: 'Explain why minimum pricing for alcohol may reduce health-related externalities.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A minimum price per unit sets a floor price, particularly affecting cheap, high-strength drinks favoured by heavy drinkers. 1 mark: Heavy drinkers tend to have more price-elastic demand for cheap alcohol, so they reduce consumption most. 1 mark: Reduced heavy drinking lowers health externalities (NHS costs, alcohol-related crime, workplace absenteeism) while having minimal effect on moderate drinkers who already pay above the minimum price.' },
      { q: 'Explain why government intervention to correct market failure may itself lead to government failure.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Imperfect information - the government may lack sufficient data to set the optimal tax rate, subsidy level, or regulation. 1 mark: Unintended consequences - policies may create perverse incentives or distort markets in unexpected ways. 1 mark: Administrative costs - the cost of implementing, monitoring, and enforcing intervention may exceed the benefit. 1 mark: Political pressures - decisions may be influenced by lobbying, electoral considerations, or bureaucratic self-interest rather than efficiency, leading to outcomes worse than the original market failure.' },
      { q: 'Explain one reason why public goods cannot be efficiently allocated by the price mechanism.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: The price mechanism requires excludability - the ability to prevent non-payers from consuming. 1 mark: Since public goods are non-excludable, consumers have no incentive to reveal their true willingness to pay (free rider problem), making it impossible for the market to determine the efficient quantity or charge an appropriate price.' },
      { q: 'Explain how extending property rights over carbon emissions could help reduce climate change.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: By creating a property right to emit carbon (carbon permits), the atmosphere is no longer treated as a free resource. 1 mark: A cap-and-trade system limits total emissions and requires firms to hold permits, making carbon emissions a cost of production. 1 mark: Firms face incentives to reduce emissions (sell spare permits for profit or avoid buying costly permits), and the market price of permits reflects the scarcity of the right to pollute, driving innovation in clean technology.' },
      { q: 'Explain why buffer stock schemes designed to stabilise agricultural prices often fail.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: When prices are low, the government buys surplus to raise prices, storing the produce. 1 mark: When prices are high, the government sells from the stockpile to lower prices. 1 mark: Storage costs can be very high, especially for perishable goods, making the scheme expensive. 1 mark: If there are consecutive years of surplus, stockpiles grow unsustainably large, the scheme runs out of funds, and the guaranteed price may discourage efficiency improvements - leading to government failure.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by quasi-public goods and give one example.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Quasi-public goods possess some but not all characteristics of public goods - they may be partially non-rival or partially non-excludable. 1 mark: Valid example with explanation, e.g., roads are non-excludable but rivalrous at peak times (congestion makes them rival); or parks are non-excludable but become rival when overcrowded.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a congestion charge aims to correct the market failure associated with urban driving.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Urban driving generates negative externalities including congestion, pollution, and noise that are not reflected in the private cost of driving. 1 mark: A congestion charge internalises these external costs by making motorists pay to enter congested areas, raising the private cost to reflect the social cost. 1 mark: This reduces demand for driving in peak hours, lowering congestion and pollution, and generates revenue that can fund public transport alternatives.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the provision of healthcare is considered a market failure issue.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Information failure - consumers cannot easily assess the quality of medical treatment or judge which treatments they need (information asymmetry between doctor and patient). 1 mark: Merit good argument - healthcare is under-consumed if left to the market because people may underestimate the benefits (e.g., preventive care, vaccinations). 1 mark: Positive externalities - vaccinations protect the wider community through herd immunity; a healthier workforce is more productive. 1 mark: Equity concerns - ability to pay should not determine access to essential healthcare; a purely market-based system would leave the poor without treatment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why state provision of a good may lead to productive inefficiency.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Without the profit motive and competitive pressure, state-run providers face weaker incentives to minimise costs. 1 mark: This may lead to X-inefficiency, overstaffing, slow adoption of technology, and bureaucratic waste, meaning resources are not used as efficiently as they would be under private sector competition.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against banning single-use plastics.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: For - a ban directly eliminates the negative externality (plastic pollution in oceans, harm to wildlife), providing certainty of outcome that taxes or nudges cannot guarantee. 1 mark: Development - the environmental damage is severe and potentially irreversible, justifying a strong regulatory response. 1 mark: Against - a ban removes consumer choice and may impose disproportionate costs on businesses, especially small firms that rely on cheap packaging. 1 mark: Development - consumers may substitute with alternatives that have higher carbon footprints (e.g., cotton bags need thousands of uses to offset their production emissions), potentially creating new environmental problems.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how a cap-and-trade scheme for carbon emissions sets a socially optimal level of pollution.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing the marginal abatement cost (MAC) curve and the market for permits with a fixed supply (vertical supply of permits at the cap). 1 mark: The government sets the total cap at the socially optimal emissions level. 1 mark: Firms with low abatement costs reduce emissions and sell spare permits; firms with high abatement costs buy permits. 1 mark: The permit price equals the marginal abatement cost across all firms, ensuring the target is met at the lowest total cost to the economy, and the cap can be tightened over time to progressively reduce emissions.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.1': {
    name: 'National Economic Performance',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define inflation.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: A sustained increase in the general price level of goods and services in an economy over time.' },
      { q: 'State two components of aggregate demand.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any two from: consumption (C), investment (I), government spending (G), net exports (X-M).' },
      { q: 'Define the output gap.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: The difference between actual GDP and potential GDP (full capacity output). 1 mark: A positive output gap means actual exceeds potential (inflationary); negative means actual is below potential (deflationary/recessionary).' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of using CPI to measure inflation.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - it is internationally comparable (used across EU and OECD) and regularly updated. 1 mark: Development - allowing meaningful comparisons of inflationary pressures between countries. 1 mark: Disadvantage - it does not include housing costs (mortgage interest payments, council tax). 1 mark: Development - this means it may understate the cost of living for homeowners and distort the true inflation experience of many households.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of a fall in consumer confidence on the economy.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with initial equilibrium. 1 mark: AD shifts left (consumers spend less and save more). 1 mark: New equilibrium shows lower real GDP and lower price level (or lower inflation), with possible increase in unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Explain two consequences of deflation for an economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Consumers may delay purchases expecting further price falls, reducing aggregate demand. 1 mark: Development - this creates a deflationary spiral as falling demand causes further price cuts. 1 mark: The real value of debt increases, making borrowing more expensive in real terms. 1 mark: Development - this discourages investment and may cause bankruptcies, further reducing economic activity and employment.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the claimant count and the Labour Force Survey as measures of unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Claimant count measures those claiming unemployment-related benefits (JSA/Universal Credit). 1 mark: LFS (ILO measure) surveys households and counts those without work, available to work, and actively seeking work in the past 4 weeks. 1 mark: The LFS gives a higher figure because it includes those unemployed but not claiming benefits (e.g., those ineligible or too discouraged to claim).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a current account deficit might not be a problem for a rapidly growing economy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The deficit may reflect high investment imports (capital goods, technology) that boost future productive capacity. 1 mark: Rapid growth attracts foreign capital inflows that willingly finance the deficit. 1 mark: As the economy develops and becomes more productive, it may generate export surpluses in the future to repay foreign borrowing - the deficit is part of a development strategy rather than a sign of weakness.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain the concept of a negative output gap.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram showing LRAS (or trend output). 1 mark: Actual output (determined by AD and SRAS intersection) shown to the left of potential output. 1 mark: The gap between actual and potential output represents spare capacity - associated with unemployment above the natural rate and downward pressure on inflation.' },
      { q: 'Explain why GDP growth does not necessarily lead to a reduction in inequality.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: GDP growth measures total output increase but says nothing about distribution. 1 mark: Growth may be concentrated in sectors employing high-skilled/high-income workers (finance, technology). 1 mark: Without redistributive policies, the benefits of growth can accrue disproportionately to capital owners and high earners, widening the gap between rich and poor even as average income rises.' },
      { q: 'Calculate real GDP growth if nominal GDP rises from £2000bn to £2100bn and inflation is 2%.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Nominal growth = 5% [(2100-2000)/2000 x 100]. 1 mark: Real growth = approximately 3% (nominal growth - inflation = 5% - 2%).' },
      { q: 'Explain why structural unemployment is difficult to reduce through demand-side policies alone.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Structural unemployment arises from a mismatch between workers\' skills and job requirements. 1 mark: Increasing aggregate demand does not solve this mismatch - firms still cannot find suitably skilled workers. 1 mark: Supply-side policies (retraining, education, mobility assistance) are needed to address the fundamental skills gap and geographical/occupational immobility.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the balance of payments must always balance.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A current account deficit must be matched by a financial/capital account surplus (and vice versa). 1 mark: This is because any excess of imports over exports must be paid for either by borrowing from abroad, selling assets to foreigners, or running down foreign exchange reserves - these are recorded in the financial account.' },
      { q: 'Explain one consequence of a positive output gap for the economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A positive output gap means the economy is operating above its sustainable capacity. 1 mark: This creates demand-pull inflationary pressure as aggregate demand exceeds aggregate supply, leading to rising prices, potential wage-price spirals, and overheating that may require contractionary policy.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the HDI might be considered a better indicator of development than GDP per capita.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: HDI includes health (life expectancy) and education (years of schooling) alongside income. 1 mark: This captures dimensions of wellbeing that GDP alone misses. 1 mark: A country could have high GDP per capita but poor health outcomes or low educational attainment (e.g., some oil-rich states), which HDI would reveal as a development gap.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of hysteresis in the context of unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Hysteresis means that cyclical unemployment can become structural over time. 1 mark: Long-term unemployed workers lose skills, confidence, and work habits, making them less employable even when demand recovers. 1 mark: This effectively raises the natural rate of unemployment, meaning the economy cannot return to its previous employment level without specific supply-side interventions.' },
      { q: 'Explain two costs of inflation to an economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Menu costs - firms must frequently update prices, catalogues, and vending machines. 1 mark: Development - this diverts resources from productive activities. 1 mark: Shoe-leather costs - individuals and firms spend time and resources managing cash holdings to minimise the erosion of purchasing power. 1 mark: Development - people make more frequent trips to banks/ATMs and use complex financial instruments, representing a deadweight loss of economic efficiency.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a falling unemployment rate might not indicate an improving labour market.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: People may be leaving the labour force entirely (becoming economically inactive) rather than finding work. 1 mark: Underemployment (workers wanting more hours) is not captured. 1 mark: Zero-hours contracts and gig economy work may count as employment despite offering insecure, low-paid, and insufficient work - disguising the true health of the labour market.' },
      { q: 'Explain why PPP-adjusted GDP figures are preferred for international comparisons of living standards.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Market exchange rates do not reflect differences in the cost of living between countries. 1 mark: PPP adjustments account for how much local currency is needed to buy the same basket of goods, giving a more accurate picture of relative purchasing power and material living standards.' },
      { q: 'Explain the relationship between the current account balance and the exchange rate.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A current account deficit means more currency is being sold (to buy imports) than bought (by exporters). 1 mark: This creates downward pressure on the exchange rate under a floating system. 1 mark: The depreciation should then help correct the deficit by making exports cheaper and imports dearer (assuming Marshall-Lerner condition holds), creating a self-correcting mechanism.' },
      { q: 'Define gross domestic product (GDP).', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The total monetary value of all finished goods and services produced within a country\'s borders in a given time period.' },
      { q: 'State one cause of demand-pull inflation.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid cause, e.g., excessive consumer spending fuelled by credit, large increases in government spending, significant rise in net exports, or sharp increases in the money supply.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of a significant rise in world oil prices on the UK economy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with initial equilibrium. 1 mark: SRAS shifts left (higher production costs for firms). 1 mark: New equilibrium shows higher price level and lower real GDP. 1 mark: Explanation that this represents cost-push inflation combined with falling output (stagflation), creating a policy dilemma as reducing inflation via higher interest rates would further reduce output.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between demand-pull and cost-push inflation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Demand-pull inflation is caused by aggregate demand growing faster than aggregate supply, pulling up the general price level (too much money chasing too few goods). 1 mark: Cost-push inflation is caused by rising costs of production (wages, raw materials, energy) pushing up the price level, often shown as a leftward shift of SRAS.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a persistent current account deficit may be a cause for concern.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: It must be financed by capital inflows (selling domestic assets to foreign buyers or borrowing). 1 mark: This creates external debt that requires future interest payments, worsening the income account. 1 mark: It may reflect a fundamental lack of competitiveness in the economy. 1 mark: Reliance on foreign capital makes the economy vulnerable to sudden capital flight if investor confidence falls, potentially triggering a currency crisis.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between cyclical and frictional unemployment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Cyclical (demand-deficient) unemployment is caused by a downturn in the business cycle - insufficient aggregate demand means firms need fewer workers. 1 mark: Frictional unemployment is the short-term unemployment that occurs as workers move between jobs, enter the workforce, or search for better positions - it exists even when the economy is at full employment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why economic growth can lead to environmental degradation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Growth increases production which uses more natural resources (fossil fuels, minerals, deforestation for farmland). 1 mark: Higher output generates more pollution (carbon emissions, industrial waste, water contamination). 1 mark: Without environmental regulation, the market fails to account for these external costs, meaning GDP growth overstates genuine improvements in welfare when environmental damage is considered.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of net immigration on the aggregate supply of an economy.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with LRAS. 1 mark: LRAS shifts right as the labour supply and productive capacity of the economy increase. 1 mark: This results in higher potential output, and if immigrants are also consumers, AD may also shift right, leading to higher actual output with possibly stable prices.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between nominal and real GDP.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Nominal GDP is measured at current market prices and includes the effect of price changes (inflation). 1 mark: Real GDP adjusts for inflation by using constant (base year) prices, giving a more accurate measure of actual output changes over time.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Phillips curve illustrates a potential trade-off between inflation and unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The short-run Phillips curve shows an inverse relationship between inflation and unemployment. 1 mark: When unemployment falls, labour becomes scarce, pushing up wages and therefore costs and prices (inflation rises). 1 mark: Policymakers face a trade-off: reducing unemployment through demand-side stimulus may increase inflation, and reducing inflation through contractionary policy may increase unemployment. However, the long-run Phillips curve may be vertical at the natural rate.' },
      { q: 'Explain why GDP does not capture the value of unpaid work in the economy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: GDP only measures goods and services traded in markets at recorded prices. 1 mark: Unpaid work such as childcare, housework, voluntary community service, and subsistence farming is not included, meaning GDP underestimates total economic activity, particularly in developing countries where informal and household production is significant.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a depreciation of the exchange rate may not improve the current account balance in the short run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The J-curve effect - in the short run, import and export contracts are already agreed, so volumes do not adjust immediately. 1 mark: The depreciation makes imports more expensive in domestic currency, so the import bill rises before volumes fall. 1 mark: Over time, as contracts are renegotiated, export volumes rise and import volumes fall (assuming Marshall-Lerner condition is met), eventually improving the current account - but the initial effect is a worsening.' },
      { q: 'Explain why GDP per capita may overstate living standards in a country with high inequality.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: GDP per capita is an average that divides total output by population, so it does not reveal how income is distributed. 1 mark: If income is heavily concentrated among a small elite, the majority may have living standards well below the per capita average, meaning GDP per capita gives a misleading impression of typical welfare.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show how an increase in government spending can close a negative output gap.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram showing negative output gap (actual output below LRAS). 1 mark: AD shifts right due to increased government spending. 1 mark: Real GDP increases towards potential output, closing the gap. 1 mark: Price level may rise somewhat but the main effect is on real output when there is spare capacity, with unemployment falling as firms hire more workers.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the underground (shadow) economy creates problems for measuring GDP accurately.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The underground economy includes unreported cash transactions, illegal activities, and tax evasion. 1 mark: Since these are not declared, they are not captured in official GDP statistics. 1 mark: This means GDP understates the true level of economic activity, potentially leading to misguided policy decisions based on inaccurate data about the economy\'s real size and growth rate.' },
      { q: 'Explain two factors that determine the level of consumption in an economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Disposable income - higher income increases the ability to consume; the marginal propensity to consume determines how much of each extra pound is spent. 1 mark: Development - consumer confidence affects willingness to spend; optimistic consumers spend more from any given income. 1 mark: Interest rates - lower rates reduce the cost of borrowing and the incentive to save, encouraging consumption. 1 mark: Development - asset prices (house prices, share prices) affect consumption through the wealth effect; rising house prices make homeowners feel wealthier and more willing to spend.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the natural rate of unemployment is not zero.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Frictional unemployment always exists as workers move between jobs and take time to search for the best match. 1 mark: Structural unemployment arises from mismatches between skills workers have and skills employers need. 1 mark: These exist even when the economy is at full employment (where the labour market is in equilibrium); the natural rate is the unemployment rate consistent with stable inflation and represents an economy operating at potential output.' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of the Human Development Index (HDI) as a measure of development.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid limitation identified, e.g., HDI does not capture inequality within a country (two countries with same HDI may have very different distributions of health, education, and income). 1 mark: Development - it also excludes important dimensions such as political freedom, environmental quality, security, and gender equality, meaning it gives an incomplete picture of human wellbeing.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a recession in a major trading partner would affect the UK economy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A recession reduces the trading partner\'s demand for UK exports (their import demand falls). 1 mark: This reduces UK aggregate demand through lower net exports (X-M), leading to lower GDP growth. 1 mark: Export-dependent industries (manufacturing, financial services) face declining orders, leading to job losses and possible secondary effects on consumer confidence and investment in the UK.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the likely effect of a significant increase in labour productivity on the UK economy.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with initial LRAS and SRAS. 1 mark: LRAS shifts right as the productive capacity of the economy increases. 1 mark: SRAS also shifts right because unit labour costs fall when each worker produces more output. 1 mark: New equilibrium shows higher real GDP and a lower price level (or lower inflation), demonstrating that productivity growth enables non-inflationary economic growth and improves international competitiveness.' }
    ]
  },
  '2.2': {
    name: 'Macroeconomic Policy',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define monetary policy.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The use of interest rates, money supply, and other central bank tools to influence aggregate demand, inflation, and economic activity.' },
      { q: 'State the current inflation target of the Bank of England.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: 2% CPI inflation (with a symmetric target - equally concerned about deviations above and below).' },
      { q: 'Define an automatic stabiliser.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Fiscal mechanisms that automatically adjust government spending and taxation without deliberate policy decisions. 1 mark: They counter-cyclically dampen economic fluctuations, e.g., unemployment benefits rise in recession (boosting spending) and tax revenue rises in boom (dampening spending).' },
      { q: 'Explain how a reduction in interest rates is expected to increase aggregate demand.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Lower mortgage payments increase disposable income for homeowners, boosting consumption. 1 mark: Cheaper borrowing costs encourage business investment in capital goods. 1 mark: Lower returns on savings discourage saving and encourage spending. 1 mark: The exchange rate may depreciate as capital outflows increase, boosting net exports (X-M).' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show the effect of an expansionary fiscal policy on the economy.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with initial equilibrium. 1 mark: AD shifts to the right (due to increased G or reduced T). 1 mark: New equilibrium shows higher real GDP and higher price level.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the value of the multiplier if the marginal propensity to consume is 0.6.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Multiplier = 1/(1-MPC). 1 mark: = 1/(1-0.6) = 1/0.4 = 2.5.' },
      { q: 'Explain why fiscal policy may have a longer implementation lag than monetary policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Fiscal policy requires political processes - parliamentary approval, budget preparation, and democratic debate. 1 mark: Infrastructure spending requires planning permission, tendering, and construction time. 1 mark: Monetary policy can be changed at monthly MPC meetings and transmitted quickly through financial markets, while fiscal changes may take months or years to design, approve, and implement.' },
      { q: 'Explain how quantitative easing is intended to stimulate economic activity.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: The Bank of England creates electronic money to buy government bonds from financial institutions. 1 mark: This increases banks\' reserves, encouraging them to lend more to businesses and consumers. 1 mark: Buying bonds pushes up bond prices and reduces yields (long-term interest rates), making borrowing cheaper. 1 mark: Higher asset prices create positive wealth effects that encourage spending, and lower borrowing costs stimulate investment.' },
      { q: 'Explain one supply-side policy the government could use to increase labour productivity.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid policy identified, e.g., increased investment in education and skills training. 1 mark: Mechanism explained - better-educated workers are more productive, can use technology more effectively, and can adapt to changing economic demands. 1 mark: This shifts LRAS to the right, increasing potential output without inflationary pressure, and is a sustainable source of long-run growth.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the multiplier might be smaller during a period of high inflation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: During high inflation, the Bank of England is likely to raise interest rates. 1 mark: Higher interest rates discourage borrowing and spending, increasing the withdrawal from the circular flow. 1 mark: Additionally, if the economy is near capacity, extra spending may lead to price rises rather than output increases, reducing the real multiplier effect as nominal GDP growth is mostly inflation rather than real growth.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, illustrate the effects of cost-push inflation.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with initial equilibrium. 1 mark: SRAS shifts to the left (costs rise). 1 mark: New equilibrium shows higher price level but lower real output (stagflation), with possible increase in unemployment.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against the Bank of England being independent from government.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: For - independence reduces political business cycle problems where governments inflate before elections. 1 mark: Development - credibility keeps inflation expectations anchored, reducing the cost of achieving low inflation. 1 mark: Against - reduces democratic accountability over a key economic tool. 1 mark: Development - unelected officials making decisions that significantly affect employment, growth, and income distribution without direct public mandate or scrutiny.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the liquidity trap and its implications for monetary policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A liquidity trap occurs when interest rates are at or near zero and cannot be cut further. 1 mark: At this point, increasing money supply has no effect because banks hold reserves rather than lend, and consumers/firms prefer to hold cash rather than invest. 1 mark: Monetary policy becomes ineffective ("pushing on a string"), requiring alternative tools like QE or fiscal policy to stimulate demand.' },
      { q: 'Explain why supply-side policies alone cannot solve a recession caused by a collapse in aggregate demand.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Supply-side policies increase productive capacity (potential output) by shifting LRAS right. 1 mark: But in a demand-deficient recession, the problem is insufficient spending, not insufficient capacity. 1 mark: Increasing potential output does not help if actual demand is far below current capacity - demand-side stimulus is needed first to close the negative output gap, with supply-side policies supporting long-run recovery.' },
      { q: 'Explain how fiscal austerity might make a recession worse through the multiplier.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Cutting government spending reduces aggregate demand directly. 1 mark: The multiplier amplifies this - reduced income leads to reduced consumer spending, which reduces business revenue, leading to further job losses. 1 mark: In a recession, the multiplier may be larger (spare capacity, constrained monetary policy), meaning austerity causes a proportionally greater fall in GDP than the initial spending cut.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between discretionary fiscal policy and automatic stabilisers.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Discretionary fiscal policy involves deliberate government decisions to change spending or taxation levels (e.g., budget announcements). 1 mark: Automatic stabilisers are built-in mechanisms that operate without new decisions (e.g., progressive taxes automatically reduce take-home income in booms and unemployment benefits automatically increase spending in recessions).' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of using GDP growth as the primary target of macroeconomic policy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: GDP growth may conflict with other objectives such as environmental sustainability or equality. 1 mark: Development - pursuing growth may increase carbon emissions, deplete resources, or primarily benefit high earners, raising questions about whether growth alone improves social welfare.' },
      { q: 'Explain how forward guidance works as a monetary policy tool.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Forward guidance involves the central bank communicating its likely future interest rate path to markets and the public. 1 mark: If the Bank signals rates will stay low, businesses are more confident to invest and consumers more willing to borrow, boosting current spending. 1 mark: It works by managing expectations - reducing uncertainty about future borrowing costs, which is especially important at the zero lower bound when actual rate cuts are impossible.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the long-run effect of a successful supply-side policy.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with LRAS. 1 mark: LRAS shifts to the right (increased productive capacity). 1 mark: New long-run equilibrium shows higher potential output and lower price level (or at least non-inflationary growth), with no conflict between growth and inflation objectives.' },
      { q: 'Explain why Keynesian economists advocate government spending during recessions rather than tax cuts.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Government spending directly enters the circular flow as injection, with a multiplier of 1/(1-MPC). 1 mark: Tax cuts may be saved rather than spent (especially by cautious consumers in recession), reducing the effective multiplier. 1 mark: Government can target spending at areas with highest multipliers (infrastructure, employment programmes) and ensure the money circulates, whereas tax cuts rely on private decisions that may not stimulate demand if confidence is low.' },
      { q: 'Define fiscal policy.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The use of government spending and taxation to influence aggregate demand, the level of economic activity, and the distribution of income.' },
      { q: 'State one example of a supply-side policy.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid example, e.g., investment in education and training, deregulation of labour markets, reduction in corporation tax, infrastructure spending, or trade union reform.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a budget deficit and the national debt.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A budget deficit occurs when government spending exceeds tax revenue in a single year (a flow concept). 1 mark: The national debt is the total accumulated stock of government borrowing over time - it is the sum of all past budget deficits minus any surpluses.' },
      { q: 'Explain how raising the national minimum wage could affect unemployment.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: If set above the market equilibrium wage, it creates a surplus of labour (more workers willing to work at the higher wage than firms wish to employ). 1 mark: This may increase unemployment, particularly among low-skilled and young workers whose marginal revenue product is below the new minimum. 1 mark: However, monopsony employers may actually employ more workers at a higher minimum wage. 1 mark: The overall effect depends on the elasticity of labour demand, the size of the increase, and whether the labour market is competitive or monopsonistic.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a government might pursue a policy of privatisation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Privatised firms face profit incentives and competitive pressure, encouraging greater efficiency and innovation. 1 mark: Sale of state assets generates one-off revenue for the government that can reduce debt or fund public services. 1 mark: Private ownership may improve management quality through market discipline, the threat of takeover, and shareholder accountability, addressing X-inefficiency common in state enterprises.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show how a contractionary monetary policy can reduce inflation.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram with initial equilibrium at a high price level. 1 mark: AD shifts left as higher interest rates reduce consumption and investment. 1 mark: New equilibrium shows lower price level (or lower rate of inflation) but also lower real GDP, illustrating the trade-off between controlling inflation and maintaining output/employment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why fiscal policy may crowd out private sector investment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Increased government borrowing to finance spending raises demand for loanable funds. 1 mark: This pushes up interest rates in financial markets. 1 mark: Higher interest rates discourage private sector investment and consumption, potentially offsetting the stimulus effect of government spending - meaning the net increase in aggregate demand is smaller than intended.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against using progressive taxation to reduce inequality.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: For - progressive taxation takes a higher proportion of income from high earners, raising revenue to fund public services and transfers that benefit the poor. 1 mark: Development - this directly reduces post-tax income inequality and funds welfare programmes that improve social mobility. 1 mark: Against - high marginal tax rates may discourage work effort, entrepreneurship, and risk-taking. 1 mark: Development - this can reduce economic growth and tax revenue (Laffer curve argument), and high earners may engage in tax avoidance or relocate to lower-tax jurisdictions, undermining the policy\'s effectiveness.' },
      { q: 'Explain how deregulation of the labour market is intended to reduce unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Deregulation reduces restrictions on hiring and firing, making employers more willing to take on workers as the risk and cost of employment falls. 1 mark: Removing minimum wage regulations or reducing employment rights allows wages to adjust to market-clearing levels. 1 mark: Greater labour market flexibility improves the matching of workers to jobs and reduces structural unemployment, though critics argue it creates insecure, low-quality employment.' },
      { q: 'Explain the transmission mechanism through which a change in the Bank Rate affects the economy.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: The Bank of England changes the Bank Rate (the rate at which it lends to commercial banks). 1 mark: Commercial banks adjust their lending and saving rates in response. 1 mark: This affects borrowing costs for consumers (mortgages, personal loans) and firms (business loans), changing consumption and investment levels. 1 mark: The exchange rate is also affected (higher rates attract foreign capital, appreciating the pound), influencing net exports. All channels feed through to aggregate demand and ultimately to output, employment, and inflation.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the term "fiscal drag".', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Fiscal drag occurs when inflation pushes nominal incomes into higher tax brackets without any real increase in purchasing power. 1 mark: This increases the average tax burden on individuals without a deliberate policy decision, effectively reducing real disposable income and acting as an automatic brake on aggregate demand.' },
      { q: 'Explain why there may be conflicts between macroeconomic policy objectives.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Reducing unemployment through expansionary policy may increase inflation (Phillips curve trade-off). 1 mark: Pursuing economic growth may worsen the current account deficit as rising incomes suck in imports. 1 mark: Policies to reduce inflation (higher interest rates) may slow growth and increase unemployment. 1 mark: These conflicts mean policymakers cannot achieve all objectives simultaneously and must prioritise, making trade-offs between short-run and long-run goals.' },
      { q: 'Explain how investment in infrastructure can act as both a demand-side and supply-side policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Demand-side: the spending itself directly increases aggregate demand and creates employment during the construction phase (multiplier effects). 1 mark: Supply-side: once completed, better infrastructure (roads, broadband, railways) reduces business costs and increases productivity. 1 mark: This shifts both AD right in the short run and LRAS right in the long run, making it uniquely effective in addressing both cyclical and structural economic challenges.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a government might choose to reduce corporation tax as a supply-side policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Lower corporation tax increases post-tax profits, giving firms greater retained earnings for investment. 1 mark: It makes the country more attractive for foreign direct investment, increasing capital stock and productive capacity. 1 mark: Higher investment shifts LRAS right, increasing potential output and long-run growth, though critics argue the revenue forgone could have funded public services that also improve supply-side capacity.' },
      { q: 'Explain one risk of relying on monetary policy alone to manage the macroeconomy.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Monetary policy may become ineffective in a liquidity trap when interest rates are at or near zero and cannot be cut further. 1 mark: Additionally, monetary policy operates mainly through interest rates and credit channels, which may not reach all parts of the economy equally - for example, higher interest rates may harm the housing sector disproportionately while having limited effect on cash-rich multinational firms.' },
      { q: 'Explain why Friedman and monetarist economists argue that excessive growth in the money supply causes inflation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The quantity theory of money (MV = PQ) suggests that if velocity (V) and output (Q) are relatively stable, an increase in money supply (M) leads to a proportional increase in the price level (P). 1 mark: Monetarists argue that governments funding deficits by printing money increase M without corresponding increases in output. 1 mark: This excess money bids up prices as consumers and firms try to spend more than the economy can produce, causing demand-pull inflation; therefore controlling the money supply is key to controlling inflation.' },
      { q: 'Using an AD/AS diagram, show how an economy can recover from a recession without government intervention.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn AD/AS diagram showing a recessionary position (AD intersecting SRAS to the left of LRAS). 1 mark: In recession, unemployment pushes wages down, reducing firms\' costs. 1 mark: Lower costs shift SRAS right. 1 mark: Eventually, the economy returns to the full-employment level of output at a lower price level, illustrating the classical/monetarist argument for self-correcting markets - though Keynesians argue wages are sticky downwards, making this process slow and painful.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a government might find it difficult to reduce its budget deficit during a recession.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Automatic stabilisers increase spending (more unemployment benefits) and reduce revenue (less income and corporation tax) during recession. 1 mark: Cutting spending or raising taxes to close the deficit would further reduce aggregate demand, worsening the recession (pro-cyclical policy). 1 mark: This creates a policy dilemma: reducing the deficit is contractionary, but allowing it to grow risks rising debt and higher future interest payments, constraining future fiscal flexibility.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which supply-side policies can help reduce inflation without increasing unemployment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Supply-side policies such as investment in education, deregulation, or infrastructure shift LRAS right. 1 mark: This increases the productive capacity of the economy, allowing higher output to be produced at the same or lower price level. 1 mark: Unlike demand-side contractionary policies that reduce inflation by reducing output and employment, supply-side improvements enable non-inflationary growth - reducing inflation while maintaining or increasing employment.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the size of the budget deficit if government spending is £850bn and tax revenue is £790bn, and explain one reason why the deficit might widen during a recession.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Budget deficit = £850bn - £790bn = £60bn. 1 mark: During a recession, automatic stabilisers increase the deficit because tax revenues fall (lower incomes, profits, and spending reduce income tax, corporation tax, and VAT receipts). 1 mark: Simultaneously, government spending on unemployment benefits and other transfers rises automatically, further widening the gap between spending and revenue without any deliberate policy change.' }
    ]
  },
  '3.1': {
    name: 'Business Economics',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term "sunk costs".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Costs that have been incurred and cannot be recovered if the firm exits the market (e.g., advertising expenditure, specialist equipment with no resale value).' },
      { q: 'State the formula for average total cost.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: ATC = Total Cost / Output, or equivalently ATC = AFC + AVC.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between fixed costs and variable costs.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Fixed costs do not change with output in the short run (e.g., rent, insurance). 1 mark: Variable costs change directly with the level of output (e.g., raw materials, direct labour).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the relationship between marginal cost and average cost.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn U-shaped AC and MC curves. 1 mark: MC crosses AC at the minimum point of the AC curve. 1 mark: Explanation that when MC < AC, AC is falling; when MC > AC, AC is rising; they intersect at the minimum of AC (mathematical relationship - the average is pulled down by a lower marginal and up by a higher marginal).' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm might continue to produce in the short run even when making a loss.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If price is above average variable cost, the firm covers all variable costs and contributes something towards fixed costs. 1 mark: If it shut down, it would still have to pay fixed costs in the short run, making losses even greater. 1 mark: Therefore, it minimises losses by continuing to produce as long as P > AVC, but would exit in the long run if losses persist.' },
      { q: 'Explain two types of internal economies of scale available to a car manufacturer.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Technical economies - large-scale assembly lines with automated robots reduce unit costs; larger factories exploit indivisibilities. 1 mark: Development - these capital-intensive techniques are only viable at high output levels, giving large manufacturers significant cost advantages. 1 mark: Purchasing economies - bulk buying of steel, glass, rubber, and components at discounted prices. 1 mark: Development - suppliers offer volume discounts because large orders reduce their own per-unit costs of processing and delivery.' },
      { q: 'Explain the law of diminishing returns and its effect on short-run costs.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The law states that as more units of a variable factor (labour) are added to a fixed factor (capital), eventually the marginal product of the variable factor will fall. 1 mark: Falling marginal product means each additional worker adds less to output. 1 mark: This causes marginal cost to rise (paying the same wage for less additional output) and eventually average variable cost and average total cost to rise, creating the U-shaped short-run cost curves.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the long-run average cost curve is sometimes called the "envelope curve".', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: The LRAC curve is tangent to (touches) each possible short-run average cost curve. 1 mark: It "envelopes" all the SRAC curves because for each level of output, the firm can choose the optimal plant size, and the LRAC shows the minimum cost achievable at each output when all factors are variable.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm with significant market power might choose revenue maximisation rather than profit maximisation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Revenue maximisation occurs where MR = 0 (output is higher than profit max). 1 mark: Managers may prefer this because higher sales/revenue enhances their prestige, salary (often linked to turnover), and job security. 1 mark: The principal-agent problem means managers can pursue this objective when shareholders cannot perfectly monitor their behaviour, especially in large firms with dispersed ownership.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the container principle gives rise to technical economies of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: The volume of a container (capacity) increases more rapidly than its surface area when dimensions increase. 1 mark: Therefore, doubling the surface area (and roughly doubling material costs) more than doubles the capacity - meaning average cost of storage/transport per unit falls as scale increases (e.g., oil tankers, warehouses, pipes).' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the profit-maximising output and supernormal profit for a firm.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with AR, MR, MC, and AC curves. 1 mark: Profit-maximising output identified where MC = MR. 1 mark: Supernormal profit shown as shaded area between AR and AC at the profit-maximising output (area = (AR - AC) x Q).' },
      { q: 'Explain why diseconomies of scale might arise as a firm grows very large.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Coordination problems - as the firm grows, it becomes harder to manage different departments and ensure they work together efficiently. 1 mark: Communication difficulties - information takes longer to flow through many layers of hierarchy and may be distorted. 1 mark: Motivation and morale - workers in very large organisations may feel alienated and unimportant, reducing effort and productivity.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between normal profit and supernormal profit.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Normal profit is the minimum return needed to keep the entrepreneur in the industry (covers opportunity cost) - TR = TC including normal profit. 1 mark: Supernormal (abnormal) profit exists when TR > TC (including normal profit) - the firm earns more than the opportunity cost of capital and enterprise.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the threat of takeover can help align the interests of managers and shareholders.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If managers pursue their own objectives at the expense of profit, the firm becomes undervalued relative to its potential. 1 mark: This makes it attractive to corporate raiders who can buy shares cheaply and replace management. 1 mark: The threat of being removed incentivises managers to perform well and maximise shareholder value, partially resolving the principal-agent problem.' },
      { q: 'Calculate average fixed cost, average variable cost, and average total cost if total fixed cost is £100, total variable cost is £400, and output is 50 units.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: AFC = £100/50 = £2 per unit. 1 mark: AVC = £400/50 = £8 per unit. 1 mark: ATC = (£100 + £400)/50 = £10 per unit (or AFC + AVC = £2 + £8 = £10).' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between internal and external economies of scale.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Internal economies of scale arise from the growth of the individual firm (e.g., bulk buying, technical specialisation). 1 mark: External economies of scale benefit all firms in an industry or area due to the growth of the industry as a whole (e.g., skilled labour pool, specialist suppliers, knowledge spillovers in a cluster).' },
      { q: 'Explain why the minimum efficient scale matters for barriers to entry.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: MES is the output level at which LRAC is first minimised. 1 mark: If MES is large relative to market demand, new entrants must enter at high scale to be cost-competitive. 1 mark: This requires massive capital investment and market share capture from day one, creating a significant barrier as the risk of failure is high and incumbent firms have cost advantages if the entrant cannot immediately achieve MES.' },
      { q: 'Explain why firms in different market structures may have different objectives.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: In perfect competition, firms must profit maximise (MR=MC) to survive as they earn only normal profit in the long run. 1 mark: Monopolists with secure market power may satisfice or pursue growth, as there is no competitive pressure forcing profit maximisation. 1 mark: In oligopoly, interdependence means firms may prioritise market share or stability over short-term profit. 1 mark: The degree of separation between ownership and control also matters - firms with dispersed shareholders and professional managers are more likely to deviate from profit maximisation.' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of a firm pursuing sales maximisation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - higher sales can increase market share, achieve economies of scale, build brand recognition, and deter potential entrants through scale. 1 mark: Disadvantage - if the firm sells beyond the point where AR = AC, it will make losses, and shareholders may object if profits are sacrificed; the firm may need to earn at least normal profit to survive long-term.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the concept of opportunity cost relates to the definition of economic profit.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Economic profit includes the opportunity cost of all resources used, including the entrepreneur\'s time and capital. 1 mark: Normal profit represents this opportunity cost - what could be earned in the next best alternative. Economic (supernormal) profit only exists when returns exceed all opportunity costs, unlike accounting profit which ignores implicit costs.' },
      { q: 'Define the term "marginal cost".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The addition to total cost of producing one more unit of output (MC = change in TC / change in Q).' },
      { q: 'State the profit-maximising condition for a firm.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: MC = MR (marginal cost equals marginal revenue), provided MC is rising through MR.' },
      { q: 'Calculate total profit if a firm sells 200 units at a price of £15 and average total cost is £12.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Profit per unit = AR - ATC = £15 - £12 = £3. 1 mark: Total profit = £3 x 200 = £600.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm in a perfectly competitive market cannot earn supernormal profit in the long run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If existing firms earn supernormal profits, new firms are attracted by potential returns and there are no barriers to entry. 1 mark: Entry of new firms increases market supply, driving down the market price. 1 mark: This process continues until price falls to the level of average cost and only normal profit is earned, removing the incentive for further entry.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of satisficing and why firms might pursue this objective.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Satisficing means achieving a satisfactory level of profit rather than the maximum possible profit. 1 mark: Managers may lack perfect information about revenue and cost conditions, making true profit maximisation impossible in practice. 1 mark: The principal-agent problem means managers may prioritise their own goals (leisure, job security, prestige) as long as profits are sufficient to keep shareholders content and avoid takeover threats.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the shut-down point for a firm in the short run.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with MC, AVC, and ATC curves. 1 mark: Shut-down point identified at the minimum of the AVC curve (where MC crosses AVC). 1 mark: Explanation that if price falls below this point, the firm cannot even cover its variable costs and losses are greater by continuing to produce than by shutting down.' },
      { q: 'Explain why financial economies of scale benefit large firms.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Large firms can borrow at lower interest rates because lenders perceive them as lower risk (diversified revenue streams, more assets as collateral). 1 mark: They also have access to a wider range of funding sources (bond markets, share issues, commercial paper) that are unavailable to small firms, reducing their cost of capital and giving them a competitive advantage in funding investment.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the short run and the long run are defined differently in economics compared to calendar time.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: In economics, the short run is defined as the period in which at least one factor of production is fixed (typically capital/plant size). 1 mark: The long run is when all factors of production are variable. The actual calendar time this takes varies by industry - for a hairdresser the long run may be weeks, while for a power station it may be decades.' },
      { q: 'Explain how managerial economies of scale arise in large firms.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Large firms can afford to employ specialist managers for each function (marketing, finance, operations, HR). 1 mark: This division of managerial labour increases efficiency and decision quality compared to small firms where one manager handles multiple roles, reducing average costs as the cost of specialist managers is spread over a large output.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between the short-run and long-run production decisions of a firm making losses.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: In the short run, the firm continues to produce if P > AVC because it covers variable costs and contributes towards fixed costs (which must be paid regardless). 1 mark: In the long run, all costs become variable, so the firm will exit the market if P < ATC as it cannot cover all costs. 1 mark: The distinction matters because fixed costs create a sunk cost in the short run that makes continued production rational even at a loss, but this incentive disappears when contracts expire and capital can be redeployed.' },
      { q: 'Explain why vertical integration might reduce a firm\'s costs.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Vertical integration (merging with suppliers or distributors) eliminates transaction costs such as negotiating contracts, search costs, and mark-ups charged by intermediaries. 1 mark: It gives the firm greater control over supply chains, reducing uncertainty about input quality, delivery times, and prices. 1 mark: It can also prevent the double marginalisation problem where each stage of the supply chain adds its own profit margin, raising the final price above the jointly optimal level.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by predatory pricing and why competition authorities are concerned about it.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Predatory pricing involves a dominant firm deliberately setting prices below cost to drive competitors out of the market. 1 mark: The firm absorbs short-run losses, relying on financial reserves to outlast smaller rivals. 1 mark: Once competitors exit, the firm raises prices and exploits monopoly power, reducing consumer welfare and competition. This is illegal under UK competition law because it harms long-run consumer interests despite appearing to benefit them in the short run.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a natural monopoly has a continuously falling long-run average cost curve.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing LRAC falling throughout the relevant range of market demand. 1 mark: Demand curve intersects LRAC while it is still falling. 1 mark: Explanation that extremely high fixed costs and low marginal costs mean average costs continue to fall as output increases, making it more efficient for one firm to supply the entire market rather than having multiple firms duplicate the fixed infrastructure.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the principal-agent problem is more severe in large public limited companies than in sole proprietorships.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: In a sole proprietorship, the owner is the manager, so there is no separation of ownership and control - interests are naturally aligned. 1 mark: In large PLCs, ownership is dispersed among thousands of shareholders who cannot directly monitor managerial decisions. 1 mark: Managers may exploit this information asymmetry to pursue personal objectives (empire building, perks, risk aversion) at the expense of profit maximisation, leading to X-inefficiency and suboptimal shareholder returns.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between horizontal and vertical integration.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Horizontal integration is a merger or acquisition between firms at the same stage of production in the same industry (e.g., two car manufacturers merging), aiming to increase market share and achieve economies of scale. 1 mark: Vertical integration is between firms at different stages of production (e.g., a brewery buying a pub chain), aiming to secure supply chains, reduce costs, and control distribution.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm might pursue a strategy of diversification.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Diversification (conglomerate integration) involves expanding into unrelated markets or product areas. 1 mark: It reduces risk because poor performance in one market can be offset by strong performance in another (portfolio effect). 1 mark: It may also allow the firm to exploit synergies in management expertise, brand reputation, or financial resources, and provides growth opportunities when the existing market is mature or saturated.' },
      { q: 'Calculate marginal cost if total cost rises from £500 to £580 when output increases from 10 to 12 units.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Change in TC = £580 - £500 = £80; change in Q = 12 - 10 = 2. 1 mark: MC = £80 / 2 = £40 per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the concept of creative destruction is important for understanding the benefits of competition.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Creative destruction (Schumpeter) describes the process by which innovative firms replace less efficient incumbents through new products, technologies, or business models. 1 mark: This process drives long-run productivity growth as resources shift from declining firms to more efficient ones. 1 mark: Competition ensures firms must continually innovate or face exit, benefiting consumers through better products and lower prices, even though individual firms and workers may suffer during the transition.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show a firm earning a loss but still producing in the short run.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with AR, MR (below AR if imperfect competition), MC, AVC, and ATC curves. 1 mark: Price (AR) shown above AVC but below ATC. 1 mark: Profit-maximising (loss-minimising) output at MC = MR. 1 mark: Loss area shown as the rectangle between ATC and AR at the chosen output level, with explanation that the firm continues because the loss is smaller than the fixed costs it would bear by shutting down.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a firm experiencing external diseconomies of scale might see its long-run average costs rise even if its own output has not changed.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: External diseconomies of scale arise from the growth of the industry as a whole, not the individual firm. 1 mark: As the industry expands, competition for inputs (skilled labour, raw materials, land) drives up factor prices for all firms. 1 mark: Congestion, strain on local infrastructure, and increased regulatory costs also raise average costs, meaning even a firm maintaining constant output faces higher per-unit costs due to the external environment worsening.' }
    ]
  },
  '3.2': {
    name: 'Market Structures & Competition',
    questions: [
      { q: 'State two characteristics of a perfectly competitive market.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any two from: many buyers and sellers, homogeneous products, perfect information, free entry and exit, firms are price takers.' },
      { q: 'Define productive efficiency.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Producing at the minimum point of the average cost curve, where no resources are wasted and output cannot be increased without increasing inputs.' },
      { q: 'State one difference between a monopoly and an oligopoly.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid difference, e.g., a monopoly has one dominant firm while oligopoly has a few large interdependent firms; or monopoly has no close substitutes while oligopolists\' products may be differentiated or homogeneous.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the long-run equilibrium of a firm in perfect competition.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with AR=MR (horizontal demand), MC, and AC curves. 1 mark: Equilibrium where MC = MR = AR = AC (all at minimum AC). 1 mark: Firm earns normal profit only (no incentive to enter or exit). Allocative efficiency (P=MC) and productive efficiency (P=min AC) both achieved.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopolist can earn supernormal profit in the long run.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: High barriers to entry (patents, economies of scale, brand loyalty, legal restrictions). 1 mark: These prevent new firms from entering the market even when they observe supernormal profits. 1 mark: Therefore competitive forces that would erode profits in contestable markets do not operate, allowing the monopolist to maintain P > AC indefinitely.' },
      { q: 'Explain why firms in oligopolistic markets are described as "interdependent".', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: There are few large firms, each with significant market share, so one firm\'s actions directly affect rivals\' profits and behaviour. 1 mark: Each firm must therefore consider how rivals will react before making pricing, output, or marketing decisions - creating strategic behaviour that is absent in other market structures.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain the concept of deadweight welfare loss in monopoly.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn monopoly diagram with AR, MR, MC curves. 1 mark: Monopoly output at MR=MC, price on AR curve above this. 1 mark: Competitive output at AR=MC (P=MC) shown for comparison. 1 mark: Deadweight loss triangle identified between competitive and monopoly output, between demand curve and MC - representing lost consumer and producer surplus from reduced output.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the kinked demand curve model predicts price rigidity in oligopoly.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If a firm raises price, rivals do not follow - the firm loses many customers (elastic demand above kink). 1 mark: If a firm cuts price, rivals match the cut - the firm gains few extra customers (inelastic demand below kink). 1 mark: This creates a discontinuity in the MR curve at the kink, meaning MC can shift within this gap without changing the profit-maximising price, explaining price stickiness.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the CMA might assess whether a proposed merger would reduce competition.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: The CMA examines whether the merger creates or enhances a substantial lessening of competition (SLC). 1 mark: It considers market definition, combined market share, and the HHI concentration index. 1 mark: It assesses barriers to entry - if new firms can easily enter, market power may be constrained. 1 mark: It evaluates potential consumer harm (higher prices, reduced quality, less innovation) against claimed efficiencies and whether these would be passed on to consumers.' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of price discrimination for consumers.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - some consumers pay less than they would under uniform pricing. 1 mark: Development, e.g., student discounts make rail travel or cinema affordable for those with low incomes who otherwise could not access the service. 1 mark: Disadvantage - consumers with inelastic demand pay more than the uniform price. 1 mark: Development, e.g., peak-time commuters who must travel at certain times face much higher prices, and their consumer surplus is extracted by the firm.' },
      { q: 'Explain why excess capacity exists in long-run equilibrium under monopolistic competition.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Product differentiation gives each firm a downward-sloping demand curve. 1 mark: Long-run equilibrium occurs where AR is tangent to AC (normal profit), but this tangency point is to the left of minimum AC. 1 mark: The firm therefore produces below the output that minimises average costs - this represents excess capacity that would not exist under perfect competition (where the tangency is at minimum AC).' },
      { q: 'Explain how contestability theory suggests a monopoly could still produce efficient outcomes.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: If barriers to entry and exit are low (especially low sunk costs), potential entrants can make "hit-and-run" entry. 1 mark: The monopolist cannot charge supernormal profits because this would attract entry. 1 mark: To deter entry, the monopolist must price at or near average cost and operate efficiently - producing outcomes similar to competition despite being the sole firm (P approaches AC, approaching allocative and productive efficiency).' },
      { q: 'Explain how game theory applies to advertising decisions in a duopoly.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Each firm must decide whether to advertise heavily or not, considering the rival\'s likely response. 1 mark: If both advertise, costs rise but market shares may remain unchanged (prisoners\' dilemma - both worse off than if neither advertised). 1 mark: But if one advertises and the other does not, the advertiser gains significant market share. The dominant strategy for both may be to advertise, even though mutual non-advertising would be more profitable.' },
      { q: 'Explain why natural monopolies pose a problem for competition policy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Natural monopolies have such large minimum efficient scale that one firm can supply the market at lower cost than multiple firms (e.g., water pipes, railway tracks). 1 mark: Breaking them up would raise average costs as each smaller firm loses economies of scale. 1 mark: But leaving them unregulated allows exploitation of monopoly power. This creates a dilemma: competition policy cannot simply promote rivalry; instead, regulation (price caps, quality standards) must substitute for competitive pressure.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how third-degree price discrimination works in the airline market.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Two sub-market diagrams drawn (e.g., business vs leisure travellers) with different elasticities. 1 mark: Business travellers have inelastic demand (higher price charged). 1 mark: Leisure travellers have elastic demand (lower price charged). 1 mark: Profit maximisation in each sub-market where MR = MC in that segment, with higher prices where demand is less elastic.' },
      { q: 'Explain why collusion between firms in an oligopoly tends to be unstable.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Each firm has an individual incentive to cheat - by secretly cutting prices or producing above quota, it can gain market share and extra profit. 1 mark: Detection of cheating may be difficult, especially with many products or fluctuating demand that masks individual firm deviations. 1 mark: Cartels are illegal in most countries, making formal enforcement impossible and creating risks of prosecution and heavy fines that further destabilise agreements.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which digital markets differ from traditional market structure models.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid difference identified, e.g., network effects create increasing returns to scale where the product becomes more valuable with more users (social media, platforms). 1 mark: This leads to "winner-take-all" dynamics and natural dominance that is self-reinforcing, unlike traditional models where diseconomies of scale eventually limit firm size.' },
      { q: 'Explain why X-inefficiency is more likely in a monopoly than in a competitive market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A monopolist faces no competitive pressure because barriers to entry protect its market position. 1 mark: Without the threat of losing customers to rivals, there is less incentive to minimise costs - managers may allow organisational slack, excessive perks, or inefficient practices, operating above the minimum possible average cost curve.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a two-part tariff works and why firms use it.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A two-part tariff consists of a fixed fee (membership/access charge) plus a per-unit price for consumption. 1 mark: Example: gym membership plus pay-per-class, or theme park entry fee plus ride charges. 1 mark: The fixed fee captures consumer surplus that a single uniform price cannot access, while the per-unit price can be set at or near marginal cost to encourage consumption - increasing the firm\'s total revenue and profit beyond what uniform pricing achieves.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against breaking up large technology companies.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: For - large tech firms use network effects and data advantages to dominate markets, stifling competition and innovation by smaller rivals. 1 mark: Development - consumers face limited choice and may pay through higher prices, reduced privacy, or lower quality when competitive pressure is absent. 1 mark: Against - the efficiency of these firms depends on scale (data, network effects), and breaking them up would destroy the very features that make their products valuable. 1 mark: Development - innovation may be reduced if firms cannot achieve sufficient scale to fund R&D, and consumers may lose convenience and interoperability.' },
      { q: 'Define allocative efficiency.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The condition where price equals marginal cost (P = MC), meaning resources are allocated to produce the combination of goods and services that consumers most value, and no reallocation could make anyone better off without making someone else worse off.' },
      { q: 'State two conditions necessary for price discrimination to be possible.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: The firm must have market power (be a price maker, not a price taker). 1 mark: The firm must be able to separate consumers into distinct groups with different price elasticities of demand and prevent resale (arbitrage) between groups.' },
      { q: 'Explain why non-price competition is common in oligopolistic markets.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Price competition is risky in oligopoly because rivals are likely to match price cuts, leading to price wars that reduce profits for all firms. 1 mark: Non-price competition (branding, advertising, loyalty schemes, product quality, after-sales service) allows firms to differentiate their products and attract customers without triggering destructive price wars. 1 mark: This enables firms to build brand loyalty, which creates a barrier to entry and reduces the price elasticity of demand for their product, supporting higher long-run profits.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the long-run equilibrium of a firm under monopolistic competition.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with downward-sloping AR and MR curves, U-shaped AC and MC curves. 1 mark: Profit-maximising output at MC = MR. 1 mark: AR curve tangent to AC curve at the profit-maximising output (earning normal profit only). 1 mark: Output shown to the left of minimum AC, illustrating excess capacity and productive inefficiency, with P > MC showing allocative inefficiency.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of limit pricing and how it deters entry.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Limit pricing involves an incumbent firm setting price below the profit-maximising level but above its own average cost. 1 mark: The price is set low enough that potential entrants, facing higher average costs (no economies of scale yet), could not earn normal profit at this price. 1 mark: This sacrifices some short-run profit to maintain long-run market dominance by making entry appear unprofitable, acting as a strategic barrier to entry.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between first-degree and third-degree price discrimination.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: First-degree (perfect) price discrimination charges each consumer their maximum willingness to pay, extracting all consumer surplus. 1 mark: Third-degree price discrimination charges different prices to different identifiable groups based on elasticity of demand (e.g., students vs adults). 1 mark: First-degree is rarely achievable in practice as firms cannot know each individual\'s reservation price, while third-degree is common (age-based discounts, peak/off-peak pricing) as it only requires segmenting the market into broad groups.' },
      { q: 'Explain how RPI-X regulation works for natural monopolies.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: RPI-X is a price cap where the regulated firm can only increase prices by the rate of inflation (RPI) minus an efficiency factor (X). 1 mark: The X factor represents expected efficiency gains, forcing the firm to reduce real prices over time. 1 mark: The firm keeps any profits from exceeding the efficiency target, creating an incentive to cut costs beyond the minimum required. However, setting X too high may reduce investment and quality, and too low allows excessive profits.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopoly may have greater incentive to innovate than a perfectly competitive firm.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Supernormal profits provide the financial resources (retained earnings) to fund expensive R&D programmes. 1 mark: The monopolist can capture the full returns from innovation through patents and barriers to entry, unlike competitive firms where innovations are quickly copied. 1 mark: The Schumpeterian argument suggests monopoly power is a temporary reward that incentivises breakthrough innovation, driving long-run dynamic efficiency even if static efficiency is sacrificed.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopoly market may produce less consumer choice than a monopolistically competitive market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A monopoly has one firm producing one product with no close substitutes, offering consumers limited choice. 1 mark: Monopolistic competition has many firms each offering differentiated products (different brands, styles, features), giving consumers a wide variety of options that cater to diverse preferences, even though each firm has some market power.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a concentration ratio is measured and what it indicates.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A concentration ratio measures the combined market share of the largest firms in an industry (e.g., CR5 is the market share of the five largest firms). 1 mark: A high concentration ratio (e.g., CR5 above 60%) indicates an oligopolistic market structure where a few firms dominate, suggesting potential for market power, interdependence, and possible anti-competitive behaviour.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a monopolist may choose not to maximise profit.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The monopolist may fear attracting regulatory scrutiny or government intervention (price controls, forced break-up) if profits are seen as excessive. 1 mark: The principal-agent problem may lead managers to pursue alternative objectives such as revenue maximisation, growth, or satisficing. 1 mark: The monopolist may also practise cross-subsidisation, using profits from one market to subsidise entry into another, or charge lower prices to build long-run goodwill and customer loyalty.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a monopolist sets price and output to maximise profit.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with downward-sloping AR and MR curves (MR below AR), and U-shaped MC and AC curves. 1 mark: Profit-maximising output identified where MC = MR. 1 mark: Price read off the AR (demand) curve at the profit-maximising quantity, shown to be above AC, with supernormal profit area identifiable.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of dynamic efficiency and why it matters for long-run consumer welfare.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Dynamic efficiency refers to improvements in products, processes, and technology over time, typically driven by investment in research and development. 1 mark: It leads to lower costs, better-quality products, and new goods that improve consumer welfare beyond what static efficiency alone can achieve. 1 mark: Markets with strong dynamic efficiency (technology, pharmaceuticals) may tolerate some static inefficiency (monopoly profits) because the innovation it funds ultimately benefits consumers more than the welfare loss from higher current prices.' },
      { q: 'Explain why barriers to exit can be as significant as barriers to entry for market contestability.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Barriers to exit include sunk costs (irrecoverable investments in specialised equipment, branding, or training). 1 mark: High sunk costs deter entry because potential entrants know they cannot recover their investment if they fail - making "hit-and-run" entry too risky. 1 mark: A market with low entry barriers but high exit barriers is not truly contestable, because the risk of irrecoverable losses deters the competitive threat that would otherwise discipline incumbent firms.' },
      { q: 'Explain why tacit collusion is more likely to occur in markets with few firms selling similar products.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: With few firms, each can easily observe rivals\' behaviour (prices, output), making it easier to coordinate without explicit agreement. 1 mark: Similar (homogeneous) products make it simple to adopt a common pricing strategy, often following a price leader. 1 mark: Deviation from the tacit agreement is quickly detected and punished (tit-for-tat), sustaining cooperation. In contrast, markets with many firms or highly differentiated products make monitoring and coordination much harder.' },
      { q: 'Explain one way in which monopsony power in the labour market differs from monopoly power in a product market.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Monopsony power is buyer power - a dominant employer can push wages below the competitive equilibrium because workers have few alternative employers. 1 mark: Monopoly power is seller power - a dominant firm restricts output and raises price above marginal cost. Both reduce allocative efficiency, but monopsony exploits workers (lower wages, fewer employed) while monopoly exploits consumers (higher prices, less output).' },
      { q: 'Explain why product differentiation is the key feature that distinguishes monopolistic competition from perfect competition.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: In perfect competition, products are homogeneous (identical), so firms are price takers with perfectly elastic demand. 1 mark: In monopolistic competition, each firm produces a slightly differentiated product (brand, design, location), giving it a small degree of market power and a downward-sloping demand curve, allowing it to set its own price within a limited range.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the prisoners\' dilemma model helps explain why oligopolistic firms may compete on price even when it reduces total industry profit.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: In the prisoners\' dilemma, each firm has a dominant strategy to cut prices regardless of what the rival does. 1 mark: If both cooperate (maintain high prices), both earn high profits. 1 mark: But each firm fears that the rival will undercut them, gaining market share at their expense. 1 mark: The Nash equilibrium is for both firms to compete on price, even though this yields lower profits than cooperation - each firm acts in its own self-interest, leading to a collectively suboptimal outcome.' },
      { q: 'Define dynamic efficiency.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Efficiency achieved over time through innovation, research and development, and technological progress that improves products, reduces costs, or creates entirely new goods and services.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a perfectly competitive market achieves allocative efficiency in long-run equilibrium.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram with horizontal AR = MR (demand) curve at the market price, and U-shaped MC and AC curves. 1 mark: Long-run equilibrium at MC = MR = AR = minimum AC, with price equal to marginal cost (P = MC). 1 mark: Explanation that P = MC means the value consumers place on the last unit (price) equals the cost of producing it (marginal cost), so resources are allocated to their most valued use and no reallocation could improve welfare.' }
    ]
  },
  '4.1': {
    name: 'International Economics & Globalisation',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term "globalisation".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: The increasing integration and interdependence of world economies through growth in trade, capital flows, migration, and spread of technology and ideas.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage of specialisation according to comparative advantage.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Countries can produce and consume beyond their production possibility frontier through trade, increasing total world output and consumer choice.' },
      { q: 'Define a floating exchange rate.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: An exchange rate system where the value of the currency is determined by market forces (supply and demand for the currency in foreign exchange markets). 1 mark: Without direct government or central bank intervention to fix or control the rate.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the welfare effects of free trade compared to autarky (no trade).', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing domestic supply and demand with world price below domestic equilibrium. 1 mark: Under free trade, domestic production falls, consumption rises, and imports fill the gap. 1 mark: Consumer surplus increases (larger triangle above world price), though producer surplus falls; net welfare gain shown as the difference (trade creation triangles).' },
      { q: 'Explain two reasons why a country might impose tariffs on imported goods.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Protect domestic industries and jobs - tariffs raise import prices, making domestic goods relatively competitive. 1 mark: Development - this may be justified for infant industries or strategic sectors like defence. 1 mark: Raise government revenue - tariffs generate income for the state. 1 mark: Development - this is particularly important for developing countries where income tax collection is difficult and trade taxes are administratively simpler.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between trade creation and trade diversion in the context of the EU.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Trade creation occurs when EU membership allows members to import from lower-cost EU partners instead of producing domestically at higher cost. 1 mark: Trade diversion occurs when the common external tariff forces members to buy from higher-cost EU producers instead of cheaper non-EU sources. 1 mark: The EU is welfare-enhancing only if trade creation exceeds trade diversion across all goods and members.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a depreciation of the pound affects the foreign exchange market.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly labelled forex diagram with supply and demand for pounds, price of pounds in foreign currency on y-axis. 1 mark: Either supply of pounds shifts right (UK buyers need foreign currency) or demand for pounds shifts left (reduced foreign demand). 1 mark: New equilibrium shows a lower exchange rate (pound buys less foreign currency), correctly labelled.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the terms of trade matter for developing countries dependent on primary exports.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Terms of trade = (export price index / import price index) x 100. 1 mark: If primary product prices decline relative to manufactured goods prices (Prebisch-Singer hypothesis), developing countries must export more to afford the same imports. 1 mark: This means deteriorating terms of trade effectively transfer real income from developing to developed countries, making it harder to import capital goods needed for development.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a trading bloc can affect non-member countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Trade diversion - the common external tariff may make non-member exports more expensive than less efficient member exports, diverting trade away from efficient non-members. 1 mark: Loss of market access - non-members face tariffs while members trade freely, reducing non-members\' export competitiveness. 1 mark: The bloc may use its collective bargaining power in trade negotiations to extract concessions from non-members, potentially disadvantaging smaller countries.' },
      { q: 'Explain why hot money flows can cause problems for a country with a floating exchange rate.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Hot money is short-term capital that moves rapidly in response to interest rate differentials or speculation. 1 mark: Sudden inflows cause rapid appreciation, harming export competitiveness. Sudden outflows cause rapid depreciation, increasing import costs and potentially triggering inflation. 1 mark: This volatility creates uncertainty for businesses making trade and investment decisions, and exchange rate movements may not reflect fundamental economic conditions.' },
      { q: 'Explain one benefit and one cost of FDI for a developing host country.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Benefit - technology transfer and skill development as MNCs bring advanced techniques, management practices, and training. 1 mark: Development - this increases productivity of domestic firms through spillover effects and raises the skills base of the workforce. 1 mark: Cost - profit repatriation means a significant portion of earnings flows back to the MNC\'s home country. 1 mark: Development - this creates a drain on the current account and means the host country captures less of the value created, potentially contributing to dependency and limited domestic capital accumulation.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the Marshall-Lerner condition and its significance.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The condition states that a depreciation will improve the trade balance only if the sum of PED for exports and PED for imports is greater than one. 1 mark: If met, the volume effects of cheaper exports and dearer imports outweigh the price effects (paying more per unit of import). 1 mark: Significance: if the condition is not met, depreciation worsens the trade balance because demand is so inelastic that volume changes are insufficient to offset higher import costs and cheaper export earnings per unit.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the WTO promotes most-favoured-nation (MFN) treatment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: MFN means that any trade concession granted to one WTO member must be extended to all members. 1 mark: This prevents discrimination, ensures a level playing field, promotes multilateral trade liberalisation, and prevents powerful countries from exploiting weaker ones through exclusive bilateral arrangements.' },
      { q: 'Explain two ways in which globalisation has affected income inequality within developed countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Offshoring manufacturing to low-wage countries reduces demand for low-skilled workers in developed nations. 1 mark: Development - this depresses wages at the bottom and causes structural unemployment in former industrial regions. 1 mark: Globalisation increases returns to capital, skilled labour, and education. 1 mark: Development - those with financial assets and advanced skills benefit from global markets, widening the gap between high and low earners within the same country.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a country might choose a fixed exchange rate system.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Certainty for international trade and investment - businesses can plan without exchange rate risk. 1 mark: Discipline on domestic monetary policy - prevents excessive money creation that would undermine the peg. 1 mark: Controls inflation - importing the credibility of the anchor currency and preventing competitive devaluations that could trigger inflation.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "Dutch disease" and why it can hinder development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Dutch disease occurs when a resource boom (e.g., oil discovery) causes the exchange rate to appreciate. 1 mark: The stronger currency makes non-resource exports (manufacturing, agriculture) uncompetitive on world markets. 1 mark: This causes deindustrialisation and over-reliance on the resource sector, making the economy vulnerable when resource prices fall and losing the diversification needed for sustainable development.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against the UK pursuing bilateral trade deals post-Brexit.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: For - bilateral deals can be tailored to UK priorities and fast-growing markets (e.g., tech services with the US). 1 mark: Development - the UK can negotiate terms suited to its comparative advantages without compromise needed in multilateral settings. 1 mark: Against - bilateral negotiations give less bargaining power than the EU bloc of 450 million consumers. 1 mark: Development - individual deals may offer less comprehensive coverage, take years to negotiate, and cannot replicate the depth of the EU single market with zero tariffs, harmonised regulation, and freedom of movement.' },
      { q: 'Explain how comparative advantage theory justifies free trade even when one country is more efficient at producing everything.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A country with absolute advantage in everything still has a comparative advantage in the good where its efficiency advantage is greatest (lowest opportunity cost). 1 mark: By specialising in that good and trading, both countries can consume beyond their individual production possibility frontiers. 1 mark: Total world output increases because resources are allocated to where opportunity costs are lowest, even though one country is absolutely more productive in everything.' },
      { q: 'Explain why exchange rate volatility might deter trade and investment.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Unpredictable exchange rate movements create uncertainty about the domestic currency value of future export revenues or import costs. 1 mark: This makes it difficult for firms to plan, set prices, and assess investment returns, potentially discouraging cross-border trade and long-term foreign direct investment that requires stable profit expectations.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "race to the bottom" in the context of globalisation.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: The race to the bottom describes countries competing to attract FDI by lowering labour standards, environmental regulations, or tax rates. 1 mark: Each country fears capital flight if it maintains higher standards, creating downward pressure on workers\' protections, environmental quality, and public revenue - potentially making everyone worse off despite the individual incentive to compete.' },
      { q: 'Define the term "tariff".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: A tax imposed by a government on imported goods, raising the price of imports and generating revenue for the government.' },
      { q: 'State one advantage of free trade for consumers.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid advantage, e.g., lower prices due to increased competition, greater variety of goods and services available, or access to goods not produced domestically.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of imposing a tariff on an imported good.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing domestic supply and demand with world price and domestic equilibrium. 1 mark: Tariff raises the effective import price from the world price to world price plus tariff. 1 mark: Domestic production increases and imports decrease. 1 mark: Welfare loss identified as two deadweight loss triangles (production inefficiency and consumption loss), with government revenue rectangle and transferred surplus clearly shown.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between a customs union and a free trade area.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: A free trade area removes tariffs between member countries but each member maintains its own external tariff against non-members (e.g., NAFTA/USMCA). 1 mark: A customs union removes internal tariffs and adopts a common external tariff against all non-members (e.g., the EU), requiring members to coordinate trade policy with the rest of the world.' },
      { q: 'Explain why the infant industry argument is used to justify protectionism.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Infant industries are newly established domestic industries that cannot yet compete with established foreign firms due to lack of economies of scale and experience. 1 mark: Temporary protection (tariffs or subsidies) allows them to grow, achieve lower unit costs, and develop competitive advantages. 1 mark: Once mature, protection can be removed and the industry should compete internationally. However, the argument is often abused - governments struggle to identify genuine infant industries, and protection may become permanent as industries lobby to retain it.' },
      { q: 'Explain how a managed (dirty) float exchange rate system operates.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The exchange rate is primarily determined by market forces of supply and demand. 1 mark: However, the central bank intervenes occasionally by buying or selling its own currency to influence the rate. 1 mark: Intervention aims to smooth excessive volatility, prevent misalignment, or achieve specific policy objectives, combining the flexibility of floating with some stability benefits of fixing.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a country with a comparative advantage in primary commodities may face long-run disadvantages from free trade.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Primary commodity prices tend to be volatile, creating income instability for the exporting country. 1 mark: Long-run terms of trade may deteriorate (Prebisch-Singer thesis) as commodity prices fall relative to manufactured goods. 1 mark: Specialisation in primary commodities offers limited scope for technological progress and value-added compared to manufacturing. 1 mark: Over-reliance on commodity exports (resource curse) may lead to Dutch disease, corruption, and failure to diversify, trapping the economy in low-value production.' },
      { q: 'Explain why protectionism might lead to retaliation and a trade war.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: When one country imposes tariffs, the affected country\'s exporters lose market access and face declining sales. 1 mark: The affected country may respond with its own tariffs on imports from the first country to protect its own industries and as a political response. 1 mark: This escalation can spiral into a trade war where both countries impose increasingly high barriers, reducing trade volumes, raising consumer prices, and lowering global economic welfare - as illustrated by the Smoot-Hawley tariffs in the 1930s.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between absolute and comparative advantage.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Absolute advantage means a country can produce a good using fewer resources (more efficiently) than another country. 1 mark: Comparative advantage means a country can produce a good at a lower opportunity cost than another country. A country can have comparative advantage without absolute advantage, and trade based on comparative advantage benefits both countries.' },
      { q: 'Explain how transfer pricing by multinational corporations can affect developing host countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Transfer pricing involves MNCs setting artificial prices for transactions between their subsidiaries in different countries. 1 mark: By overpricing imports from and underpricing exports to low-tax subsidiaries, MNCs shift profits away from the developing country to minimise their global tax bill. 1 mark: This reduces tax revenue for the developing country government, limits funds available for public services and infrastructure, and effectively transfers wealth from poor countries to tax havens, undermining the development benefits of FDI.' },
      { q: 'Explain why quotas may be considered more harmful than tariffs for economic efficiency.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Quotas directly restrict the quantity of imports, creating a fixed limit regardless of market conditions. 1 mark: Unlike tariffs, quotas do not generate government revenue - the difference between the domestic price and the world price (quota rent) accrues to licence holders or foreign exporters. 1 mark: Quotas remove the price signal mechanism and can create more severe distortions as they prevent any additional imports regardless of changes in domestic demand or supply conditions.' },
      { q: 'Explain the significance of the current account for an economy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The current account records trade in goods and services, primary income (investment returns), and secondary income (transfers). 1 mark: A persistent deficit indicates the country is spending more abroad than it earns, requiring financing through capital inflows or asset sales. 1 mark: This matters because it affects the exchange rate, creates external debt obligations, may signal declining competitiveness, and creates vulnerability to sudden capital outflows if investor confidence weakens.' },
      { q: 'Explain one argument for and one argument against the use of export subsidies.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: For - export subsidies help domestic firms compete in international markets by reducing their costs, enabling them to price competitively and gain market share. 1 mark: Development - this can support employment in export industries, help infant industries establish themselves, and improve the trade balance. 1 mark: Against - subsidies distort comparative advantage by making artificially cheap exports, harming efficient producers in other countries. 1 mark: Development - they impose a fiscal cost on taxpayers, may provoke retaliatory measures from trading partners, and violate WTO rules, potentially leading to trade disputes and sanctions.' },
      { q: 'Explain why deindustrialisation in developed economies is partly linked to globalisation.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Globalisation enables firms to relocate manufacturing to countries with lower labour costs (offshoring). 1 mark: Developing countries with comparative advantage in labour-intensive manufacturing gain market share, displacing domestic production in developed countries. 1 mark: This shifts developed economies towards services, reducing manufacturing employment and output as a proportion of GDP, with significant regional impacts in former industrial areas and structural unemployment among displaced workers.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by the J-curve effect and why it occurs.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The J-curve describes the pattern where a currency depreciation initially worsens the trade balance before eventually improving it. 1 mark: In the short run, import and export volumes are slow to adjust because of existing contracts, consumer habits, and supply chain inertia, but import prices rise immediately, increasing the import bill. 1 mark: Over time (months to years), volumes adjust as exports become cheaper abroad and imports become more expensive domestically, eventually improving the trade balance - the path traces a J shape on a graph of the trade balance over time.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show the effect of a quota on a market for an imported good.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing domestic supply and demand with world price. 1 mark: Quota shown as a limit on import quantity, effectively creating a new supply curve (domestic supply plus quota amount). 1 mark: Domestic price rises above world price due to restricted supply. 1 mark: Deadweight loss triangles identified, with quota rent rectangle shown (the revenue that goes to quota holders rather than the government, unlike a tariff).' },
      { q: 'Explain how remittances from migrant workers can benefit their home country\'s economy.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Remittances are money transfers sent by migrants working abroad back to their families in the home country. 1 mark: They provide a direct source of foreign currency earnings that can exceed foreign aid, improving the current account and supporting the exchange rate. 1 mark: At the household level, remittances fund consumption, education, healthcare, and small business investment, reducing poverty and stimulating local economic activity, particularly in rural areas where formal financial services are limited.' },
      { q: 'Explain one limitation of the theory of comparative advantage.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid limitation identified, e.g., the theory assumes constant opportunity costs (linear PPFs), but in reality opportunity costs are increasing due to factor specialisation. 1 mark: Development - other limitations include the assumption of perfect factor mobility within countries and immobility between them, no transport costs, no barriers to trade, and the exclusion of dynamic changes in comparative advantage over time due to technology, education, or industrial policy.' },
      { q: 'State one non-tariff barrier to trade.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid non-tariff barrier, e.g., import quotas, product standards and regulations, subsidies to domestic producers, voluntary export restraints, administrative delays, or sanitary and phytosanitary requirements.' },
      { q: 'Explain why a current account surplus is not necessarily a sign of economic strength.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A surplus may reflect weak domestic demand rather than strong export performance - consumers and firms are not spending enough, reducing import demand. 1 mark: It could indicate an undervalued exchange rate that makes exports artificially cheap, distorting trade patterns. 1 mark: Persistent surpluses may provoke trade tensions with deficit countries and indicate that the country is saving excessively rather than investing domestically, potentially sacrificing current living standards and consumption for unnecessary reserve accumulation.' }
    ]
  },
  '4.2': {
    name: 'Development & Inequality',
    questions: [
      { q: 'Define the term "economic development".', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: A process of improving the economic wellbeing and quality of life of a population, encompassing growth, poverty reduction, improved health/education, structural change, and expanded freedoms.' },
      { q: 'State one limitation of using the Gini coefficient as a measure of inequality.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid limitation, e.g., it only measures income inequality not wealth inequality; two countries can have the same Gini but very different income distributions (the curve shape matters, not just the area); it does not indicate the absolute level of income.' },
      { q: 'Distinguish between absolute poverty and relative poverty.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Absolute poverty is defined by a fixed standard below which basic human needs cannot be met (e.g., World Bank $2.15/day line). 1 mark: Relative poverty is defined in relation to the rest of society (e.g., below 60% of median national income) and reflects social exclusion rather than basic survival.' },
      { q: 'Explain two barriers to development in Sub-Saharan Africa.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Weak institutions and corruption - resources are diverted from productive investment to personal enrichment of elites. 1 mark: Development - this deters foreign investment, reduces aid effectiveness, and prevents the rule of law needed for market-based development. 1 mark: Inadequate infrastructure - limited roads, electricity, and telecommunications raise business costs. 1 mark: Development - this prevents market access for farmers, limits industrialisation, deters investment, and means health and education services cannot reach rural populations effectively.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how the Lorenz curve is used to show income inequality.', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn Lorenz curve diagram with line of perfect equality (45-degree line) and a bowed-out Lorenz curve below it. 1 mark: Axes correctly labelled (cumulative % of population on x-axis, cumulative % of income on y-axis). 1 mark: Explanation that greater distance between the Lorenz curve and the line of equality indicates greater inequality (the Gini coefficient is the ratio of the area between them to the total area below the equality line).' },
      { q: 'Explain how the Harrod-Domar model identifies savings as key to economic growth.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The model states that growth rate = savings ratio / capital-output ratio. 1 mark: Higher savings provide funds for investment in physical capital. 1 mark: Investment increases productive capacity, enabling higher output. The model implies developing countries with low savings rates will grow slowly unless foreign aid/investment fills the "savings gap" - though it is limited by ignoring diminishing returns and institutional factors.' },
      { q: 'Explain why gender inequality can act as a barrier to economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Excluding women from education reduces human capital development and limits the skills available to the economy. 1 mark: Restricting women\'s participation in the labour market reduces productive potential and GDP growth. 1 mark: Evidence shows that educated women invest more in children\'s health and education, creating intergenerational benefits - gender inequality thus perpetuates poverty cycles and limits future development potential.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of "aid dependency" and why it might hinder development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Aid dependency occurs when a country relies heavily on foreign aid for government revenue and basic services. 1 mark: This can reduce incentives to develop domestic tax systems, build productive capacity, or reform governance. 1 mark: Governments become accountable to donors rather than citizens, aid flows are unpredictable making planning difficult, and sudden aid withdrawal can cause fiscal crises - creating vulnerability rather than sustainable self-reliance.' },
      { q: 'Explain how conditional cash transfers (CCTs) attempt to break the cycle of poverty.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: CCTs provide regular payments to poor households conditional on specific behaviours (e.g., children attending school, mothers attending health check-ups). 1 mark: The immediate payment alleviates current poverty and smooths consumption. 1 mark: The conditions invest in human capital (education, health) that increases future earning potential, breaking intergenerational poverty transmission. Evidence from Brazil\'s Bolsa Familia and Mexico\'s Progresa shows improvements in school attendance and health outcomes.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between import substitution industrialisation and export-led growth strategies.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: ISI focuses on producing manufactured goods domestically to replace imports, using tariffs and subsidies to protect infant industries. 1 mark: Development - aims to reduce dependency on imported manufactures but can lead to inefficiency, rent-seeking, and limited markets. 1 mark: Export-led growth focuses on developing competitive export industries to earn foreign exchange and achieve economies of scale. 1 mark: Development - exposes firms to international competition (promoting efficiency) and provides larger markets, but requires initial comparative advantage and access to global markets. East Asian tigers succeeded with export-led; Latin American ISI had mixed results.' },
      { q: 'Explain how corruption hinders economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Corruption diverts public resources from infrastructure, health, and education to private enrichment. 1 mark: It deters foreign investment because firms face unpredictable costs and cannot rely on legal protections. 1 mark: It undermines trust in institutions, reduces tax compliance, and creates inefficient allocation of resources (contracts go to those who bribe rather than most efficient providers).' },
      { q: 'Explain why rapid economic growth in China has not eliminated inequality.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Growth has been geographically concentrated in coastal/urban areas while rural inland regions lag behind. 1 mark: Returns to education and capital have increased faster than unskilled wages, benefiting the already-advantaged. 1 mark: Institutional factors (hukou system, unequal access to services) prevent equal opportunity, and high-income groups capture disproportionate policy benefits.' },
      { q: 'Explain what is meant by "sustainable development" and why it poses challenges for developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Sustainable development meets present needs without compromising future generations\' ability to meet their needs. 1 mark: It requires balancing economic growth with environmental protection and social equity. 1 mark: Challenge: developing countries face pressure to exploit resources quickly (deforestation, mining) for immediate income and poverty reduction. 1 mark: They lack financial resources for clean technology and face unfairness arguments - developed countries industrialised without environmental constraints, yet now expect developing countries to limit their growth paths.' },
      { q: 'Explain how brain drain affects developing countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Brain drain is the emigration of highly educated/skilled workers to developed countries offering better pay and opportunities. 1 mark: This reduces the stock of human capital needed for development (fewer doctors, engineers, teachers). 1 mark: However, there are partial offsets: remittances sent home support consumption and investment, diaspora networks can facilitate trade and knowledge transfer, and some emigrants return with new skills and capital. The net effect depends on the scale of emigration relative to domestic training capacity.' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of debt relief for developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - resources previously used for debt servicing (interest and repayment) can be redirected to health, education, and infrastructure investment. 1 mark: Development - HIPC initiative countries like Tanzania and Mozambique increased social spending significantly after relief. 1 mark: Disadvantage - it may create moral hazard where countries borrow irresponsibly expecting future forgiveness. 1 mark: Development - relief without governance reform may simply enable further misallocation, and it may be unfair to countries that managed their debts responsibly.' },
      { q: 'Explain the role of institutions in promoting economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Institutions include the legal system, property rights, regulatory framework, and political structures. 1 mark: Strong institutions protect property rights (encouraging investment), enforce contracts (enabling trade), reduce corruption (improving resource allocation), and provide public goods. 1 mark: Countries with strong institutions (rule of law, accountability) tend to develop faster because economic agents face less uncertainty, transaction costs are lower, and resources flow to productive rather than rent-seeking activities.' },
      { q: 'Explain why economic growth alone may not reduce absolute poverty.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Growth may be concentrated in sectors not employing the poor (e.g., capital-intensive mining). 1 mark: Without inclusive policies, benefits may not trickle down to the poorest who lack assets, skills, or market access to participate in growth. 1 mark: Growth may increase prices of essentials (food, housing) faster than poor people\'s incomes rise, potentially worsening their material conditions despite rising average GDP.' },
      { q: 'Explain how fair trade schemes attempt to improve outcomes for producers in developing countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Fair trade guarantees a minimum price above the world market price for products like coffee, cocoa, and bananas. 1 mark: This provides income stability and protects producers from commodity price volatility. 1 mark: Additional "fair trade premiums" fund community development projects (schools, wells, healthcare), and standards require decent working conditions. However, coverage is limited and some argue it creates market distortions.' },
      { q: 'Explain one criticism of Structural Adjustment Programmes imposed on developing countries.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Valid criticism identified, e.g., forced trade liberalisation exposed infant industries to premature competition, causing deindustrialisation. 1 mark: Development - domestic firms that might have become competitive with time were destroyed by cheaper imports, reducing manufacturing employment and export diversification potential, making countries more dependent on primary commodities.' },
      { q: 'Explain how the capability approach (Amartya Sen) differs from income-based measures of development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Income-based measures (GDP per capita) focus on material resources available. 1 mark: The capability approach measures development by people\'s substantive freedoms - their ability to do and be things they value (be healthy, be educated, participate in community, live without fear). 1 mark: This is broader because two people with the same income may have very different capabilities due to discrimination, disability, or institutional barriers. It shifts focus from means (income) to ends (human flourishing) and supports policies targeting specific deprivations rather than just income growth.' },
      { q: 'Define the term "foreign direct investment" (FDI).', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Investment by a firm in one country into business operations (e.g., building a factory, acquiring a company) in another country, involving a lasting interest and significant degree of influence over the foreign enterprise.' },
      { q: 'State one characteristic that distinguishes a developing country from a developed country.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid characteristic, e.g., lower GDP per capita, higher proportion of employment in primary sector, lower life expectancy, lower adult literacy rates, weaker infrastructure, or higher infant mortality rates.' },
      { q: 'Explain why property rights are considered essential for economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Secure property rights give individuals and firms confidence that their assets and profits will not be arbitrarily seized. 1 mark: This encourages investment, savings, and entrepreneurship because people can keep the returns from their efforts. 1 mark: Without property rights, there is little incentive to invest in land improvement, build businesses, or seek credit (since property cannot be used as collateral), trapping economies in low-productivity subsistence activities.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "poverty trap" and how it perpetuates underdevelopment.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: A poverty trap is a self-reinforcing cycle where poverty itself creates conditions that prevent escape from poverty. 1 mark: Low income leads to low savings, which limits investment, which restricts productivity growth, which keeps income low. 1 mark: At the household level, poverty means poor nutrition, limited access to education and healthcare, reducing human capital formation and earning potential for the next generation, perpetuating the cycle across generations.' },
      { q: 'Explain how microfinance can promote development in low-income countries.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Microfinance provides small loans, savings facilities, and insurance to poor individuals who are excluded from traditional banking services due to lack of collateral or credit history. 1 mark: Small loans enable entrepreneurship, allowing the poor to start or expand small businesses, generating income and employment. 1 mark: Evidence suggests microfinance can empower women, reduce vulnerability to shocks, and increase household investment in education and health, though impact varies and high interest rates on some microloans are controversial.' },
      { q: 'Explain the Lewis model of economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: The Lewis dual-sector model describes a developing economy with two sectors: a traditional agricultural sector with surplus (underemployed) labour and a modern industrial sector. 1 mark: Surplus labour from agriculture is transferred to the industrial sector at a subsistence wage. 1 mark: Industrial profits are reinvested, expanding the modern sector and absorbing more labour. 1 mark: Development continues until surplus labour is exhausted and wages begin to rise across both sectors. Limitations include assuming unlimited labour supply, ignoring urban unemployment, and assuming profits are reinvested rather than consumed.' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of trade liberalisation for developing countries.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - access to larger markets enables specialisation according to comparative advantage, achieving economies of scale and attracting FDI. 1 mark: Development - this can accelerate growth, create employment in export sectors, and transfer technology and management practices. 1 mark: Disadvantage - domestic infant industries may be destroyed by competition from established foreign firms with lower costs and superior technology. 1 mark: Development - this can cause deindustrialisation, structural unemployment, and increased dependency on primary commodity exports with volatile prices and deteriorating terms of trade.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, show how a country can be caught in a low-level equilibrium trap (Harrod-Domar).', marks: 3, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn diagram showing population growth rate and income growth rate against per capita income. 1 mark: At low levels of per capita income, population growth exceeds income growth, dragging per capita income back down. 1 mark: The low-level equilibrium trap is where the economy settles, unable to generate enough savings and investment to push income growth above population growth, requiring a "big push" of investment to break free.' },
      { q: 'Explain how universal basic education can contribute to economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Education increases human capital, making workers more productive and adaptable to technological change. 1 mark: Literacy and numeracy are prerequisites for participation in the modern economy, enabling individuals to start businesses, access information, and make informed decisions. 1 mark: Education generates positive externalities - an educated population supports democratic governance, reduces birth rates (demographic transition), improves health outcomes, and enables the structural transformation from agriculture to manufacturing and services.' },
      { q: 'Explain why tied aid may be less effective than untied aid in promoting development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Tied aid requires the recipient to purchase goods and services from the donor country, regardless of whether they offer the best value for money. 1 mark: This can result in higher costs (20-30% more expensive) as the recipient cannot shop around for the cheapest or most appropriate suppliers. 1 mark: It primarily serves donor country commercial interests rather than recipient development needs, may fund inappropriate projects, and reduces local procurement that would support developing domestic industries.' },
      { q: 'Explain the concept of the "resource curse" and give an example.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The resource curse (paradox of plenty) describes the observation that countries rich in natural resources often experience slower economic development and worse governance than resource-poor countries. 1 mark: Resource wealth can lead to corruption, rent-seeking, conflict over resource revenues, Dutch disease, and neglect of other sectors. 1 mark: Example: Nigeria has vast oil reserves but experiences high poverty, corruption, environmental degradation in the Niger Delta, and economic volatility linked to oil price fluctuations.' },
      { q: 'Explain why improving healthcare access is considered both a cause and a consequence of economic development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: As a cause: healthier workers are more productive, have fewer absences, and can work longer, increasing economic output. 1 mark: Development - reducing childhood disease and malnutrition improves educational attainment, building human capital for future growth. 1 mark: As a consequence: higher incomes allow individuals and governments to spend more on healthcare, medicines, and sanitation. 1 mark: Development - economic development funds hospital construction, trains more doctors, and enables public health programmes, creating a virtuous cycle where growth and health improvements reinforce each other.' },
      { q: 'Explain how demographic transition relates to economic development.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: The demographic transition model describes how countries move from high birth and death rates (Stage 1) to low birth and death rates (Stage 4) as they develop. 1 mark: In the early stages, death rates fall first (due to improved sanitation, healthcare, nutrition) while birth rates remain high, causing rapid population growth. 1 mark: As development continues, birth rates fall (due to education, urbanisation, access to contraception, rising opportunity cost of children), eventually slowing population growth and creating a "demographic dividend" where the working-age population is large relative to dependents, boosting per capita income and savings.' },
      { q: 'Explain why corruption is more damaging to development than its direct financial cost suggests.', marks: 3, markScheme: '1 mark: Beyond direct financial losses, corruption destroys trust in institutions, discouraging both domestic and foreign investment. 1 mark: It distorts resource allocation as contracts and licences are awarded based on connections rather than efficiency, reducing economic productivity. 1 mark: It perpetuates inequality as the poor cannot afford bribes to access public services (education, healthcare, justice), while elites use corrupt systems to entrench their position, undermining social mobility and democratic accountability that are essential for inclusive development.' },
      { q: 'Explain one advantage and one disadvantage of using foreign aid to promote development.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Advantage - aid can fill the savings gap identified by the Harrod-Domar model, funding investment in infrastructure, healthcare, and education that developing countries cannot finance domestically. 1 mark: Development - emergency and humanitarian aid saves lives and stabilises fragile states, creating conditions for long-term development. 1 mark: Disadvantage - aid can create dependency, reducing incentives for governments to develop domestic tax systems and pursue difficult but necessary reforms. 1 mark: Development - aid may be misallocated due to corruption, tied to donor interests, or create Dutch disease effects if large inflows appreciate the exchange rate, undermining export competitiveness.' },
      { q: 'State one measure of inequality other than the Gini coefficient.', marks: 1, markScheme: '1 mark: Any valid measure, e.g., the Lorenz curve, the Palma ratio (share of income of top 10% divided by share of bottom 40%), the ratio of the 90th to 10th income percentile, or the share of income going to the top 1%.' },
      { q: 'Calculate the Gini coefficient if the area between the Lorenz curve and the line of equality is 0.18 and the total area under the line of equality is 0.5.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Gini coefficient = area between Lorenz curve and line of equality / total area under line of equality. 1 mark: Gini = 0.18 / 0.5 = 0.36, indicating moderate inequality (0 = perfect equality, 1 = perfect inequality).' },
      { q: 'Explain why investment in female education is considered one of the most effective development strategies.', marks: 4, markScheme: '1 mark: Educated women have fewer children, easing population pressure and accelerating the demographic transition. 1 mark: They earn higher incomes, increasing household consumption and savings. 1 mark: They invest more in their children\'s health and education, creating powerful intergenerational multiplier effects on human capital. 1 mark: At the macro level, including women in the productive workforce can increase GDP significantly (some estimates suggest up to 10-20% in low-income countries), while also improving governance and social cohesion.' },
      { q: 'Explain the difference between bilateral aid and multilateral aid.', marks: 2, markScheme: '1 mark: Bilateral aid is given directly from one government to another (e.g., UK DFID funding a specific project in Kenya), often tied to donor country interests or political objectives. 1 mark: Multilateral aid is channelled through international organisations such as the World Bank, IMF, or UN agencies, pooling contributions from multiple donors and potentially reducing political bias in allocation, though it may involve slower disbursement and higher administrative costs.' },
      { q: 'Using a diagram, explain how the Kuznets curve suggests the relationship between inequality and economic development changes over time.', marks: 4, diagram: true, markScheme: '1 mark: Correctly drawn inverted-U shaped curve with inequality (Gini coefficient) on the y-axis and GDP per capita or stage of development on the x-axis. 1 mark: In the early stages of development, inequality rises as some workers move to higher-productivity urban/industrial sectors while others remain in low-income agriculture. 1 mark: After a turning point, inequality falls as more of the population gains access to education, formal employment, and social transfers. 1 mark: Evaluation: the Kuznets curve is an empirical observation, not a law, and many countries (e.g., China, USA) have experienced rising inequality at high incomes, suggesting policy choices matter more than any automatic relationship.' }
    ]
  }
};

if (typeof module !== 'undefined' && module.exports) {
  module.exports = { ECONOMICS_EDEXCEL_B_PRACTICE };
}
